[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5
{ Welcome!   This course presents a repertoire after 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 based on the Czech Benoni.   This closed variation of the Benoni is called 'Czech' because it was popularized in the sixties by Czech grandmasters such as Vlastimil Hort.   Since then, the opening became a weapon of choice of the Romanian Chess School: Irina Bulmaga, Alexandru Segal, Victor Ciocâltea, Mihail Marin, and none other than Liviu-Dieter Nisipeanu, played the Czech Benoni with great success.  The Czech Benoni has also become a valuable weapon for masters such as Levon Aronian, Dmitry Andreikin, Yasser Seirawan, Tony Miles, and Benjamin Finegold.  You will find a lot of games by those Czech heroes all along with your reading.  Last but not least, the reigning World Champion Magnus Carlsen also tried the Czech Benoni with success.  So, why not you? }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Is the Czech Benoni a sound opening ? "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4
{ That is an important question I would like to answer before we go any further. I will try to be concise:  Theoretically:  - White has the advantage because of his space advantage @@StartBracket@@d5-pawn@@EndBracket@@. Computers don't like the Czech Benoni as they don't like the King's Indian Defense.  Practically:  - We don't try to equalize  (like with the Nimzo or the QGD)  but to imbalance the game @@StartBracket@@like in the King's Indian Defense@@EndBracket@@. We accept our position is slightly inferior because White's advantage is hard to prove for human players over the board. And we know the opening gives us a lot of chances for effective counterplay.  - We have more experience than our opponents in the arising positions. Even if your opponents are prepared to face the Czech Benoni, you will always have more experienced than them  (practical advantage)  with the structure and all the ideas related to it.  - A lot of grandmasters lost to the Czech Benoni: White's position is not easy to handle for humans. I can assure you that it will be the same with your opponents @@StartBracket@@at least over the board@@EndBracket@@.  What really matters  - The Czech Benoni suits your style: The Czech Benoni is an attacking weapon. Your main thought when you start the game is that checkmate is the end of the game. The Czech Benoni has a lot in common with the King's Indian Defense and the Benko.  The Czech Benoni makes you happy: You like the different positions you can reach out of the opening and are excited to use all the middlegame plans you know.  Conclusion:  If you have good results with the opening, and if you enjoy your games with it, there is no reason to care about the opinions of others or on computer assessments. And that should be the case with all the openings in your repertoire. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Philosophy of the course or Why You Should Play the Czech Benoni"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6
{ @@HeaderStart@@Philosophy of the course or Why you should play the Czech Benoni@@HeaderEnd@@  • Philosophy of the course  My philosophy is that core skills are the most important part of chess improvement.  The opening is important but is just a part of the game. The average club player doesn't need to learn hundreds of variations if he doesn't know what to do once he finished repeating all the theoretical moves he learned by rote.  Instead, I recommend to:  - focus on understanding the structures arising from the opening;  - know the middlegames plans you are aiming for;  - what are the important general tactical and strategical themes.  This course aims to show you those three points for the Czech Benoni.  @@HeaderStart@@Why should you play the Czech Benoni?@@HeaderEnd@@  • Easy to learn  The setup is easy to learn and often the same against everything White can try:  - we put our knight on f6;  - we put our pawns on c5, e5, and d6;  - we develop our bishop on e7 and our knight on d7.  Now, there are only three main setups for White, and we will start our effective counterplay according to what White tries.  • Practical  - Understanding is more important than rote memorization.  - Great opening for the lazy/busy players but also for the hard worker willing to work on his core skills first.  - Low on theory: there are only three main setups for White.  - You will know what you are aiming for before the game.  - Club players need to be well-prepared to face 1.e4, but also the London System, Jobava London, Veresov, Trompowsky... so having an easy way to meet 1.d4 followed by 2.c4 will save you a lot of time to study the rest of your repertoire and to work on your core skills.  • Will help you to improve your general chess understanding  - You will learn how to play in closed positions and how to use pawn breaks.  - You will learn general ideas you must know and can use in a lot of different positions.  • Excellent in fast time controls  The opening is fully playable in classical chess but gets better and better when the time control goes faster.  • Fantastic surprise weapon  The Czech Benoni is a rare opening: lots of your opponents will be shocked after 3.e5!?. This will give them a lot of room to commit mistakes in the opening or early middlegame.  And don't forget: even if your opponents are prepared  (theoretically)  to face the Czech Benoni, you will always have more experienced than them  (practically)  with the structure and all the ideas related to it. }
*

