[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "RubiChess vs. Leela Chess Zero (Inspirational Game #1) "]
[Result "*"]

{ The following inspirational game was played between Rubi  (RubiChess)  and Leela Chess Zero from the CCC 10 Qualifying @@StartBracket@@game 6@@EndBracket@@.    It is an excellent example to see the attacking/counter-attacking potential for Black in the Czech Benoni. Here, Black uses the f5-break and a typical plan from the King's Indian to crush White. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 { What time is it? Czech Benoni Time! } 4. Nc3 d6
5. e4
{ Now we have our typical structure with pawns on e4/d5/c4 against e5/d6/c5. You will findeverything you must know about this pawn structure in the chapter Key Middlegame Themes & Plans.   The main idea for Black is to break with f5  or b5. }
5... Be7 6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2 Na6
{ With the idea to prepare the b5-break with ...Nc7 followed by ...Rb8 and ...a6. }
8. Nf3 Ne8
{ The move ...b5 is not the only pawn break available for Black and Leela decides to also have the possibility to play for the ...f5 break. }
9. O-O f5 10. a3 f4
{ Winning more space on the kingside and ready to launch a kingside attack in typical King's Indian fashion. }
11. h3
{ Preventing Bg4.   11.gxf4  exf4  Black wins control over the e5-square and White's kingside is weakened. We will see more about this typical theme later in the course. }
11... g5 12. b3 Kh8
{ Leela frees the g8-square for the rook and is ready to attack on the kingside. }
13. Bb2 Nb8 { Rerouting the knight which is needed in the incoming attack. }
14. Qc2 Rg8 15. b4 b6 16. Ne1
{ Prophylaxis against g4.   16.bxc5  bxc5  −  ...b6 against b4 and then ...bxc5 against bxc5 is a typical theme in the Czech Benoni. The b5-square can be covered by ...a6, the knight on d7 can control b6 and b8 and the bishop on c8 guards b7. Thus, it is not easy at all for White to find counterplay on the queenside while Black will attack on the kingside. }
16... Nd7 17. Ne2 { White uses the pin to attack the f4-pawn. } 17... Nef6
{ Black brings a new piece on the kingside and breaks the pin. } 18. Nd3 Qe8
{ The queen is ready to come on h5 to put pressure on the h3-pawn. } 19. Rae1
Rg7 20. Rb1 Nf8 { The knight will join the incoming attack via g6. } 21. bxc5
bxc5 22. Ne1 Qh5 { The h3-pawn is under pressure. } 23. g4
{ 23.Kh2  Bxh3  24.Bxh3  g4  and Black is winning. } 23... Bxg4
{ Leela came here to attack, not retreat. } 24. hxg4 Nxg4 25. Nf3 Ng6 26. Qd3
Nf6
{ The plan ...g4, in combination with ...Nh4-f3 and ...Rag8, is coming if White does nothing. }
27. Ng3
{ White gives back the piece and will try to find counterplay on the f-file instead of waiting to be crushed. }
27... fxg3 28. fxg3 Rag8 { Everyone joins the party. } 29. Kf2 Qg4 30. Nh2 Nf4
{ No retreat!! } 31. Qf3
{ White tries to simplify the game with the exchange of queens.   A@@EndBracket@@  31.Nxg4  is well met by  31...Nxg4+  32.Kf3  Nh2+  the f1-rook will fall.  33.Ke3  Nxd3  34.Kxd3  Nxf1  35.Rxf1  and the material advantage will decide the game.   B@@EndBracket@@  31.gxf4  Qh4+  32.Ke2  gxf4  ,  the h2-knight and the g2-bishop are both under attack.  33.Bf3  Qxh2+  34.Rf2  Rg2!!  Again a beautiful move. Black is not afraid by Bxg2 at all.  35.Bxg2   B1@@EndBracket@@  35.Rf1  allows  35...Rxf2+  36.Rxf2  Qh3  ,  Black wants to play ...Rg3 next.  37.Bg2  Qxd3+  38.Kxd3  Rg3+  39.Bf3  Ng4  .  The bishop is pinned and White's rook can't move because of ...Nh2.  40.Rf1  Nh2  35...Rxg2  36.Rf1  Ng4  ,  the knight joins the attack with decisive effect.  37.Rxg2  Qxg2+  38.Kd1  Ne3+  and White's rook is lost. }
31... Qd7 { No Sir! } 32. Kg1
{ 32.gxf4  gxf4  33.Rg1  Rg3  34.Qe2  Ng4+  35.Nxg4  Bh4  ,  a powerful intermediate move.  36.Kf1  R8xg4  .  White is a piece up but is under a lots of pressure and is unable to find a move; ...f3 is coming next.  37.Bc3  37...Rg8  ,  ...f3 is coming.  38.Qh5  ,  attacking the h4-bishop and trying to prevent ...f3. But now comes  38...Qg7  ,  there is too much pressure along the g-file.  39.Qxh4  −  there is no time for this capture.  39...Rxg2  and Black's attack will end the game.   And in case of @@StartFEN@@6rk/p5qp/3p4/2pPp2Q/2P1Pp1b/P1B3r1/6B1/1R3KR1 w - - 4 39@@EndFEN@@  39.Rb2  ,  defending the g2-bishop but...  39...Rxc3  ,  the bishop on c3 was hanging.  40.Qxh4  Rc1+  41.Kf2  Qg3+  and the g1-rook is lost.  42.Qxg3  fxg3+  43.Kf3  Rxg1  . }
32... Qa4 { From g4 to a4, was that the V for Victory? } 33. gxf4 gxf4 34. Rf2
Rg3 35. Qe2 Qe8
{ The queen is coming to g6 now to attack the bishop on g2 but also the e4-pawn. }
36. Bc1 Qg6 37. Rb7 { Is it counterplay? } 37... Bd8 { Nope. } 38. Qb2
{ A@@EndBracket@@  38.Kh1  is bad because of  Nxe4  39.Bxe4  Rg1  .   B@@EndBracket@@  38.Kf1  Rh3  the bishop can't take because of the Qg1#-threat.  39.Kg1  Qh6  .  And now the h2-knight is attacked and can't move because of Rh1#. }
38... Nxe4 39. Bxf4 Nxf2 40. Bxg3 Nd3 41. Qe2 Qxg3
{ Leela managed to win back the piece and is now two pawns up. } 42. Qe4 Qe1+
43. Qxe1 Nxe1 44. Rb2 e4
{ A clever move. Before exchanging everything on g2, we give a square for our king to penetrate the opponent's camp. }
45. Re2 Nxg2 46. Rxg2 Rxg2+ 47. Kxg2 Kg7 48. Nf1 Kf6 49. Ng3 Ke5 50. Ne2 h5
{ Of course, we don't forget to push Harry. } 51. Kf2 h4 52. Kg2 e3
{ This allows Black's king to penetrate. } 53. Kf3 Bg5 54. Kg4 Bf6 55. Kf3 Kf5
{ Black gives up the e3-pawn. Next, he wants to divert White's king with the h-pawn. }
56. Kxe3 Kg4 57. Kf2 a6 58. Kg2 h3+ 59. Kh1 Kf3
{ White's central pawns are doomed. } 60. Ng1+ Ke4 61. Nxh3 Kd3 62. Ng1 Kxc4
63. Kg2 Kxd5
{ What a game by Black! There is of course no hope at all for White and he could have resigned here. Instead, the game continued for more than 50 moves because Black wanted to have some fun. }
64. Kf3 Kc4 65. Ke4 a5 66. Nf3 Bc3 67. a4 Kb4 68. Kd3 Bg7 69. Kd2 Kxa4 70. Ne1
Kb3 71. Kd1 Bc3 72. Nd3 Bd4 73. Nc1+ Kb2 74. Nd3+ Kc3 75. Nf4 a4 76. Ng2 a3 77.
Ke1 Be5 78. Ke2 Bg3 79. Kf1 c4 80. Ne3 Kd3 81. Nd5 Bh4 82. Nb4+ Kd2 83. Na2 Bf2
84. Kg2 Kc2 85. Nb4+ Kb3 86. Nc6 Bb6 87. Ne7 a2 88. Nc6 Ba7 89. Na5+ Kb4 90.
Nc6+ Kc5 91. Na5 Bb6 92. Nb7+ Kc6 93. Na5+ Bxa5 94. Kf2 a1=Q 95. Ke2 c3 96. Kd3
c2 97. Kxc2 d5 98. Kb3 d4 99. Kc2 d3+ 100. Kxd3 Qe5 101. Kc2 Qc3+ 102. Kb1 Qb3+
103. Kc1 Bd2+ 104. Kxd2 Qf3 105. Kc1 Qg2 106. Kd1 Kd5 107. Ke1 Ke4 108. Kd1 Kd3
109. Kc1 Qc2# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Shakhriyar Mamedyarov vs. Ben Finegold (Inspirational Game #2)"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following game was played between Shakriyar Mamedyarov  (2766)  vs Benjamin Finegold  (2483)  during the PRO Chess League @@StartBracket@@Round 7@@EndBracket@@. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5
{ Benjamin Finegold is one of our Czech Benoni heroes and you will find lots of his games throughout the course. }
4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3
{ The modern way to fight against the Czech Benoni. The bishop comes to d3 and White wants to develop the knight on e2 with the idea to jump on g3. Another idea is to put the pawns on h3 and g4 to prevent the ...f5 break. We will see more about those plans in the dedicated chapters. }
6... Nbd7 7. Nge2 { White wants to jump on g3. } 7... h5
{ And we push Harry to prevent White's plan! } 8. h3
{ Here the critical move is 8.h4 and we will examine this move later in the course. }
8... h4 9. Be3 Nf8
{ A typical knight manoeuver in the Czech Benoni that we also meet in the Black Lion. The knight comes to g6 where it is ready to jump on f4 at the right moment or to control the e5-square after f4/...exf4. }
10. Qd2 Ng6
{ Here White can decide to castle kingside, queenside, or to leave the king in the center.   The position is closed so the king is safe in the center and it can be a nice idea to not tell Black where the king is going. }
11. a3
{ While Black is trying to breakthrough with ...f5 or ...b5, White wants to breakthrough with b4 and f4. Like f4 @@StartBracket@@after ...exf4@@EndBracket@@ would give the e5-square to Black, White decides to play for the b4 break instead with the help of a3 and Rb1. }
11... Kf8 { The king is very safe on f8 and the rook is already active on h8. }
12. b4 b6 13. bxc5 bxc5 14. Rb1 Nh5 15. O-O Kg8
{ A useful waiting move. White's rook was lined up to the Black's king. Blacks want to place his bishop on f6 and then jump on f4 with one of his knights. }
16. Rb3 Bf6 17. Rfb1 Bd7
{ 17...Ngf4  was best.  18.Nxf4  exf4  19.Bxf4  Nxf4  20.Qxf4  Be5  21.Qe3  ,  with good compensations on the dark-squares for the pawn. }
18. Nb5 Bc8 19. Kh2
{ Not a good move because the king can be easily exposed on the dark squares after a lot of trades on f4. }
19... Nhf4
{ The good square but the wrong knight! It was better to put the other knight on f4 to prepare the ...g5 push.   19...Ngf4  ,  freeing the g-pawn. The game could have continued  20.Ng1  g5  21.Bxf4  exf4  22.Nf3  g4  ,  with chances for both sides. }
20. Bxf4 { This allows Black to take control over the central dark-squares. }
20... Nxf4
{ Black didn't take advantage of White's last move.  20...exf4  was better, to have beautiful control over the dark squares. }
21. Nxf4 { This only helps Black.  21.Nbc3  to keep the tension was best. }
21... exf4 22. Be2
{ 22.Qxf4  would be a terrible mistake in view of  22...Be5  . } 22... f3
{ This is a mistake but a very understandable one. Black was afraid of Bf3 blocking everything so decided to sac the pawn to have control over the dark squares.   Best was  22...g5  ,  with the idea to prepare the ...g4 break, followed by ...h3 to open the h-file. }
23. Bxf3 Be5+ 24. Kg1 Rh6 { Activating the rook. } 25. Bg4
{ A good move. This bishop is bad @@StartBracket@@because of the structure e4/d5/c4@@EndBracket@@ so White wants to trade it. More on this subject later in the course. }
25... Bxg4
{ A mistake according to the engine but the correct continuation after 25.a6 looks very passive for Black and gives all the initiative to White.   25...a6  26.Na7  Rxa7  27.Rb8  Rc7  28.Qa5  and Black is under pressure. }
26. hxg4 Rg6 27. f4 a6 28. fxe5 axb5 29. cxb5
{ 29.Rxb5  is a mistake that allows Black to find counterplay with  29...Rxg4  . }
29... c4 30. Rb4
{ This move is a mistake. White is not preventing the ...h3 idea anymore.  30.Rc3  is also attacking the c4-pawn but prevents h3 and should have been preferred. }
30... Rxg4 31. Qe3
{ 31.Rxc4  was best.  31...h3  32.Qe3  hxg2  33.Rb2  Rxa3  ,  diverting the queen from the e1-square.  34.Qxa3  Qh4  35.Rxg2  Qe1+  36.Kh2  Rh4+  37.Qh3  Rxh3+  . }
31... Rg3 32. Qf4 dxe5 33. Qxe5 Qb6+ 34. Kh1 { Better was  34.Kh2  Raxa3  . }
34... Qe3 { White is doomed. } 35. Kh2 Rxa3 36. Rxc4 { 36.Qf5  Qd2 } 36...
Rxg2+
{ Even faster was  36...Rh3+  37.gxh3  Qf2+  38.Kh1  Rxh3+  39.Qh2  Rxh2  . }
37. Kxg2 h3+ 38. Kf1 Qf3+
{ White resigns.   Not a game without mistakes but still a very instructive and enjoyable one.   This game is very interesting to show how building and maintaining an advantage without missing any tactics is very hard when the time control is fast because of all the counterplay allowed by our setup. Yay! }
39. Ke1 Re3+ 40. Kd2 Qf2+ 41. Kc1 Re1# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Jan Markos vs. Ni Hua (Inspirational Game #3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Be2
{ This is known as the classical setup @@StartBracket@@Be2 + Nf3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Ne8
{ This is a typical maneuver in the Czech Benoni. One of our goals is to break through with ...f5. For this reason, the knight comes to e8 where it frees the f-pawn and is ready to be fianchettoed after ...g6, ...Ng7, to help with the ...f5 break. }
9. Rb1 { White wants to break through with b4. } 9... g6 10. b4
{ 10.Bh6  was preferable. This move is always met by ...Ng7 @@StartBracket@@protecting the rook and preparing the ...f5 break@@EndBracket@@.  10...Ng7  11.Qd2  Kh8  ,  again a typical move. The king comes to h8 to free the g8-square. Now we are ready to play ...Nf6-g8 to attack White's bishop on h6 which is his good bishop @@StartBracket@@more on this subject later@@EndBracket@@.  12.Ne1  Nf6  13.Nd3  Ng8  14.Be3  f5  .  We achieved one of our main goals in the opening and White must prevent ...f4.  15.f4  exf4  16.Bxf4  g5  17.Be3  Bf6  with a very good game for Black. }
10... f5 11. exf5 { 11.bxc5  Nxc5 } 11... gxf5
{ This is a typical King's Indian recapture. Even if the d7-knight was not obstructing the c8-bishop, Black would have recaptured on f5 with the g-pawn. This allows Black to control the e4-square and ideas like ...Kg8/...Rg8, to build an attack against White's king, come to mind. }
12. bxc5 Nxc5 13. Nd2 Bf6 14. Nb3 b6 15. f4 Bd7 16. Rf3 Ng7 17. Nb5
{ Attacking the d6-pawn.   17.fxe5  Bxe5  was best. } 17... Ne4
{ The knight is centralized and defends the d6-pawn. } 18. Ba3
{ 18.Bd3  ,  trying to remove the knight from the strong e4-square is not possible because of  18...a6  19.Bxe4  fxe4  and if @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/3b2np/pp1p1b2/1N1Ppp2/2P1nP2/1N1B1R2/P5PP/1RBQ2K1 w - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Na3  Nc3  . }
18... Qe7 19. fxe5 Bxe5 20. N3d4 { This is the final mistake. } 20... a6 21.
Nc3 Qh4 22. g3 Nxc3
{ White resigned − a beautiful game by Black who almost did nothing except following a well-known plan by all the Czech Benoni players.   23.gxh4  was not working either.  23...Bxd4+  ,  ...Nxd1 is coming next and  24.Qxd4  is met by  24...Nxe2+  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Classical Variation 9.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3
{ 6.Be2 followed by 7.Nf3 is the same. } 6... Nbd7
{ We play ...Nbd7 first because we want to know if White's bishop is going on e2, Classical setup, or d3, Modern setup.   6...Nbd7  is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in our Classical setup if White plays  7.Be2  .   6...O-O  would transpose in 'What we want to avoid' where White squeezes Black with h3 + g4 ideas. }
7. Be2
{ Now we have a Classical setup @@StartBracket@@Nf3 + Be2@@EndBracket@@. In this position, the traditional move is 7...O-O. I will show you what are the main plans for Black. }
7... O-O 8. O-O { The main move for White. } 8... Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose:  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. a3
{ With 9.a3, White wants to play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@he is preparing Rb1 followed by b4@@EndBracket@@. While White will try to find counterplay on this part of the board, we will play on the kingside.  For this reason, we will use our typical regrouping plan: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7, trying to play for the ...f5 break. @@StartBracket@@PLAN A@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Kh8
{ My main recommendation. The idea is simple: We want to break with ...f5. To achieve this, we need to prepare it with ...g6 + ...Ng7. If we play 9...g6 immediately, White can play 10.Bh6.   We want White to lose a tempo. For instance, after  10.Be3  g6  11.Bh6  , then White moved his bishop twice in the opening. This is an important tempo because it avoids all the critical lines we can face with 9...g6. This is the reason why 9...Kh8! is my main recommendation. }
10. Rb1 g6 11. Bh6 Ng7 12. Qd2 Nf6
{ We are ready to harass the bishop from g4 or g8. } 13. b4
{ 13.Ne1  Ng8  14.Be3  f5  and ...f4 is coming. } 13... b6 14. Ne1 Ng8 15. Be3
f5 { And Black has no problems. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Classical Variation 9.a3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3
{ 6.Be2 followed by 7.Nf3 is the same. } 6... Nbd7
{ We play ...Nbd7 first because we want to know if White's bishop is going on e2, Classical setup, or d3, Modern setup.   6...Nbd7  is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in our Classical setup if White plays  7.Be2  .   6...O-O  would transpose in 'What we want to avoid' where White squeezes Black with h3 + g4 ideas. }
7. Be2
{ Now we have a Classical setup @@StartBracket@@Nf3 + Be2@@EndBracket@@. In this position, the traditional move is 7...O-O. I will show you what are the main plans for Black. }
7... O-O 8. O-O { The main move for White. } 8... Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose:  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. a3
{ With 9.a3, White wants to play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@he is preparing Rb1 followed by b4@@EndBracket@@. While White will try to find counterplay on this part of the board, we will play on the kingside.  For this reason, we will use our typical regrouping plan: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7, trying to play for the ...f5 break. @@StartBracket@@PLAN A@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Kh8
{ My main recommendation. The idea is simple: We want to break with ...f5. To achieve this, we need to prepare it with ...g6 + ...Ng7. If we play 9...g6 immediately, White can play 10.Bh6.   We want White to lose a tempo. For instance, after  10.Be3  g6  11.Bh6  , then White moved his bishop twice in the opening. This is an important tempo because it avoids all the critical lines we can face with 9...g6. This is the reason why 9...Kh8! is my main recommendation. }
10. Rb1 g6 11. Bh6 Ng7 12. Qd2 Nf6
{ We are ready to harass the bishop from g4 or g8. } 13. Ne1 Ng8 14. Be3 f5
{ ...f4 is coming. } 15. exf5 Nxf5 { We can take the e3-bishop next. } 16. Nd3
Nxe3 17. fxe3 Bg5 { Black has a good game. } *

