7. Be2
{ Now we have a Classical setup @@StartBracket@@Nf3 + Be2@@EndBracket@@. In this position, the traditional move is 7...O-O. I will show you what are the main plans for Black. }
7... O-O 8. O-O { The main move for White. } 8... Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose:  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. Ne1
{ White wants to relocate his knight on d3, where it can support f4 and b4. What are the consequences of this move? From f3, the knight prevented us from playing ...Bg5, but not anymore. }
9... Bg5
{ We managed to put our bad bishop on g5, and we are ready to trade it against the c1-bishop.  We want to play for the ...f5 break with our typical ideas  @@StartBracket@@...g6 - ...Ng7@@EndBracket@@.  That is everything you should know to play with confidence. The game could continue: }
10. Nd3 Bxc1 { The most simple. } 11. Qxc1 g6
{ We are ready to push ...f5 next. } 12. f4
{ This move gives Black the e5-square. } 12... exf4 13. Qxf4 Qe7 14. Bg4 Ne5
{ This is typical. Our e8-knight is a strong blockader on d6. } 15. Nxe5 dxe5
16. Qf3 Nd6 17. Bxc8 Raxc8 18. b3 f5 { Time to break through. } 19. exf5 gxf5
{ We control the e4-square and the g-file is opened for our pieces. Black had no problems in Danner, Georg 2385 - Kummer, Helmut 2250, 0-1, 1993. }
