[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. g3
{ White is transparent about the fact he wants to play the Fianchetto Variation. }
6... Na6
{ An interesting alternative. Black delays kingside castling because he has ideas with ...h5-h4. }
7. Bg2 Nc7
{ The knight is useful on c7 to help with the ...b5 rupture. It also allows waiting to see where White develops his knight. }
8. Nge2
{ The most common move in this position. But now Black is able to take the initiative. }
8... h5
{ A strong move and the reason why we played 6...Na6. Black wants to attack the fianchetto with Harry. Black threatens ...h4. }
9. h3 { This doesn't prevent ...h4. } 9... h4 10. g4 b5
{ Black can go Benko style. } 11. cxb5 a6 12. bxa6
{ 12.b6  Nb5  and Black is fine. } 12... Bxa6
{ With good compensation for the pawn. Black can castle next and is ready to play along the b-file. He also has ideas as ...Nh7 followed by ...Bg5. }
