[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Czech Benoni 4.dxe6?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. dxe6 fxe6 5. Nc3
{ The most common and natural move. But a mistake. } 5... d5
{ Grabbing the center and asking who is playing with the white pieces. Black threatens to play ...d4. }
6. cxd5 { The most common move. } 6... exd5
{ Black's position is dominant: he has the center and a lead in development. He is ready to develop all of his pieces on optimal squares. After ...O-O, the f-file is also an asset. Black's next move is ...d4. From now on, we will see how to deal with White's most common replies. }
7. Bg5
{ The most common move and a mistake. This does nothing against Black's threat to play ...d4. }
7... d4
{ Black is already much better here. We are going to see how to play against  8.Ne4  and  8.Bxf6  is alsoanalyzed in the course. }
8. Ne4 Nc6
{ A strong move. We are not afraid of Nxf6+ and Bxf6, and we invite White to take the challenge. }
9. Nxf6+ gxf6 10. Bh4
{ Trying to keep the pin against our queen but this is a terrible blunder. }
10... c4 { Our bishop is ready to give a devastating check on b4. } 11. a3
{ Trying to prevent ...Bb4+ but now comes: } 11... Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Bb4
{ White is lost. } *

