[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3 { This is the most common move to avoid 3.d5. } 3...
cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5
{ The only move to fight for an advantage.  5.Nc2  d5  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/5n2/4p3/2PN4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nb3  d5  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/5n2/4p3/2PN4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  Nc6  6.Nc3  Bb4  and Black is fine. }
5... d5
{ This is known as the Kasparov Gambit. We sacrifice a pawn to accelerate our development. }
6. cxd5 Bc5
{ Black is ready to castle next. In this position, there is one main move: } 7.
N5c3
{ White retreats to protect the pawn and not let his knight get overextended. }
7... O-O
{ In this position, White has two main moves:  8.g3  and  8.e3  .   Notes: 7.e3 followed by 8.N5c3 is the same @@StartBracket@@White has to play 8.N5c3 to defend the d5-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
8. g3 { White wants to play Bg2 and O-O next. } 8... Ng4
{ We attack the f2-pawn and don't let White achieve his plan. } 9. e3 f5
{ We are ready to play ...f4 next. } 10. Bg2
{ This is ourmodel game Costa, Jean Luc @@StartBracket@@2320@@EndBracket@@ - Polgar, Judit @@StartBracket@@2355@@EndBracket@@, 1987. }
10... f4
{ Only Black can be better here. The f4-pawn managed to undermine White's structure @@StartBracket@@g3/f2/e3@@EndBracket@@.   The f4-pawn is untouchable.  11.exf4  Bxf2+  and if @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp4pp/8/2bPp3/5pn1/2N1P1P1/PP3PBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.gxf4  exf4  .   After the logical  11.O-O  fxg3  12.fxg3  12.hxg3 is not possible because of ...Qg5-h5  11...Bxe3+  12.Bxe3  Rxf1+  14.Qxf1  Nxe3  and Black is much better.  Black has the initiative. Themodel game will give you an idea about how the game could continue. }
