[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "The structure"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/pp3ppp/3p4/2pPp3/2P1P3/8/PP3PPP/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This pawn structure is the one we are aiming for when we are playing the Czech Benoni.  White's static advantage: The d5-pawn gives White a space advantage and superior control over the center.  Black's dynamic potential: Black has two ruptures at his disposal: the ...f5 break and the ...b5 break. As in the King's Indian Defense and the Benko, those pawn breaks allow Black effective counterplay to fight for the initiative. If Black succeeds in a breakthrough in good conditions with ...f5 and/or ...b5, his dynamic potential will become a dynamic advantage. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "The rupture with ...b5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq2k1/pp3ppp/3p4/2pPp3/2P1P3/8/PP3PPP/6K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ One of the main pawn levers at Black's disposal is the ...b5 rupture. The usual method to prepare this breakthrough is to play: ...Na6-c7, ...Rb8, ...a6, and ...b5. ...Bd7 and ...Qa5 can help if necessary to achieve Black's plan. }
1... Na6 2. Kh1 Nc7 3. Kg1 Rb8 4. Kh1 a6 5. Kg1 Bd7 6. Kh1 b5 *

