[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "The main rupture with ...f5: the standard regrouping plan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/3p1n2/2pPp3/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a standard position from the Czech Benoni. Black would like to break through with ...f5. To achieve his goal, Black has at his disposal a 'standard regrouping plan' that you must know. }
1... Ne8
{ This move is multi-purpose :  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible. }
2. Kh1 g6
{ The knight is ready to come on g7, and the g6-pawn will support the ...f5 break. }
3. Kg1 Ng7 { The fianchettoed knight from g7 supports the ...f5 break too. } 4.
Kh1 f5
{ Now White has the choice between keeping the central tension or playing exf4. }
5. Bh6
{ White decides to do nothing about the central tension. Bh6 is a typical move and we have plans to get rid of this bishop.   5.exf5  gxf5  .  Now we take back with our g-pawn as it is usual to do it in the King's Indian Defense − Black has control over the e4-square, the central pawns are mobile, and the g-file is open: ...Kh8 and ...Rg8 come to mind. }
5... f4
{ We close the position as it is usual to do it in the King's Indian Defense. Here we have a typical plan to get rid of the bishop on h6. }
6. Kg1 Nf6 { We want to play ...Ng4 to get rid of White's bishop. } 7. h3
{ White prevents us to play ...Ng4 but now comes: } 7... Kh8
{ With the idea to play ...Ng8 next and White will have to play Bxg7. } 8. Kh1
Ng8 9. Bxg7+ Kxg7
{ Now the plan is simple but effective:  push Harry and Garry @@StartBracket@@...h5 + ...g5-g4@@EndBracket@@ mobilization of our pieces @@StartBracket@@...Rg8 - ...Kh8 - ...Nh6/...Nf6 etc.@@EndBracket@@
Through the course, you will see a lot of games where Black used those plans with success. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "No Pawn Breaks = No Plan: White's plan with h3 + g4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3p1n2/2pPp3/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ No Pawn Breaks = No Plan  White would like to prevent Black from playing both ...f5 and ...b5. A common plan is to play h3 + g4 to prevent the ...f5 break, and a4, to prevent the ...b5 break.  If White succeeds, Black will find himself squeezed with hard times to maneuver in a cramped position. However, we will see that this will never happen with correct play from Black. }
1... O-O
{ This is a mistake because Black doesn't prevent White's plan.  1...Nbd7  is my recommendation for the course. }
2. h3 Nbd7 3. g4
{ Now Black will have hard times breaking through with ...f5. } 3... a6
{ Trying to find counterplay with ...b5. } 4. a4
{ No ...b5 allowed either. White prevented both ...f5- and ...b5 breaks. Black is left with a cramped position.  In the course, you will find games where Black prevented White's plan with success. But because it is important to know what we want to avoid, you will also find three games where Black played in White's hands. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "The advance ...h5-h4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2b1k3/pp1nbppp/3p1n2/2pPp3/2P1P3/2NB4/PP2NPPP/2B1K3 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... h5
{ This ...h5 advance is typical and will be our main weapon to fight against the Modern setup @@StartBracket@@Bd3 + Nge2@@EndBracket@@.  We have already seen this h5 push in theInspirational game #2. The move ...h5 is played with the intentions to:  - play ...h4 next to increase our control over the dark squares  (f4 particularly)   - dissuade White from playing Neg3  (because ...h4 would come)   - undermine White's structure  (with the ...h4-h3 idea)   A typical maneuver you should know: ...Nd7-f8-g6 allows Black to have more control over the f4-square. }
2. Kf1 h4 3. Kg1 Nf8 4. Kf1 Ng6 5. Kg1 Nh5
{ ...h5-h4 followed by ...Nd7-f8-g6 are typical ideas we will see a lot through the course. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Good & Bad Bishops"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2b2b2/pp3ppp/3p4/2pPp3/2P1P3/8/PP3PPP/2B2B2 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Because of the structure, each side has a good and a bad bishop. For this reason, both sides would like to exchange their bad bishops.  Typical plans are:  For White:  - to exchange his bad bishop against Black's good one by playing g3 followed by Bh3;  - to exchange his bad bishop via g4.  For Black:  - to exchange his bad bishop against White's good one by playing ...Be7-g5. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Bad Bishop? (Useful/Active Bishop)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6rk/p2qb1r1/1p1p1n2/3Pp2p/2P1Ppp1/P1NQ3P/1R3PPN/4R2K b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black is ready to launch an attack on White's king. But Black's bishop on e7 is bad. How can we improve it? }
1... Bd8
{ An excellent move. All of Black's pieces need to work together against White's king. For this reason, Black wants to sacrifice a pawn with ...b5, to activate his bad bishop on b6.  Remember: It is not because a bishop is bad that he cannot become active/useful. }
2. Ne2 b5 3. cxb5 Bb6
{ This is not a bad bishop but a good one!  The excerpt comes from ourmodel game Akhmadeev, Vadim  (2439)  vs. Khismatullin, Denis  (2584)  , 0-1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "A common trap you must know (Bg5?)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3p1n2/2pPp1B1/2P1P3/2N5/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Each time White is playing his bishop from c1 to g5, you should watch for: }
1... Nxd5 { White is just losing a pawn. } 2. Bxe7
{ 2.Nxd5  Bxg5  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3p4/2pnp1B1/2P1P3/2N5/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.cxd5  Bxg5  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3p4/2pnp1B1/2P1P3/2N5/PP3PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Qxd5  Bxg5  . }
2... Nxe7
{ A lot of players fall for this trap in blitz but also in classical games! So it's important to be aware of it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Early f4 − A typical mistake"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/1p1nbp1p/p2p2p1/2pPp2n/2P1P3/P1NB4/1PQ1NPPP/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. f4
{ This is a natural move and is one you will face a lot in your games. However, in the majority of cases, f4 is premature and is only advantageous for Black. }
1... exf4
{ Now there is no pawn on e5. Black would like to use the e5-square for his pieces; ...Bf6 - ...Ne5 are typical ideas. }
2. Nxf4 Ng7 3. Be2 Bf6 4. Be3 Ne5
{ With good control over the dark squares. Black is ready to prepare the ...b5 breakthrough.  Popa Iuliana - Bulmaga Irina, 0-1, 2007. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Similarities with the King's Indian Defense"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rnk/p3q1np/1p1p2p1/2pPpp2/1PP1P3/P1N2N1P/3QBPP1/R2R2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The Czech Benoni and the King's Indian Defense have a lot in common. We have already seen examples where Black used the typical plan from the King's Indian Defense to crush White's king.  The reason for those similarities is simple: Black's main breakthrough to find counterplay in both openings is ...f5 because of the d6 and e5-pawns.  You must know this important plan. }
1... f4 { First step: Black closes the position. } 2. Ne1 g5
{ Step two: Black needs the help of Harry and Garry. } 3. Bg4 Bxg4 4. hxg4 h5
{ Black doesn't give any time to White. } 5. gxh5 g4 6. f3 Nxh5
{ Next step: We bring more pieces in the attack. The knight is ready to jump on g3 and the queen on h4.   6...g3  We must be careful with this kind of move because after  7.Kf1  Qh4  8.Ke2  White can run. }
7. bxc5 bxc5 8. Kf2 { White's king tries to run but it is already too late. }
8... Ng3 { The king has no escape square. } 9. Ne2
{ Trying to exchange our monster knight but now comes: } 9... Nxe4+ 10. fxe4
Qh4+ 11. g3 Qh2+ 12. Ng2 fxg3+
{ White resigns. You will find games where Black used this plan in our model games.  I strongly recommend you to study famous games in the King's Indian Defense where Black used this plan. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Similarities with Benko"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/pp2bppp/3p1n2/2pPp3/2P1P3/2N3P1/PP3P1P/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ There are few positions where Black is allowed to go Benko style. It's important to be aware of this possibility. }
1. Bh3
{ White wants to trade his bad bishop against Black's good one. This strategy is interesting. However, the knight on h3 will be misplaced, and Black will be allowed to go Benko style. }
1... Bxh3 2. Nxh3 b5 { Benko style! } 3. cxb5 a6 4. bxa6 Qd7
{ The knight is misplaced and needs to move. } 5. Ng5 Nxa6 6. h4 c4
{ A typical idea. The c5-square is free for our knight, and he would like to reach the d3-square next. ...Rfb8 is coming. }
7. Kf1 Nc5 8. Kg2 Rfb8
{ Black has good compensations for the pawn.  This example comes from our model gameDoroshkievich, Vladimir K vs. Arutiunov, Albert. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Main setups for White and our plans/ideas to fight against them"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7
{ Now, we will see White's three main setups and how Black can fight against them.  - The Classical setup  (Nf3 + Be2)   - The Modern setup  (Bd3 + Nf3/Nge2)   - The Fianchetto Variation  The knowledge of those plans combined with the Quickstarter Guide should already be enough for you to start playing and winning with the Czech Benoni.  I tried to be concise but don't be afraid about how much information you will find here. You can come back from time to time when you want to refresh your memory  (once you will be done with the course)  and/or after your games to check if you used the correct plans. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "The Classical Variation (Nf3 + Be2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3
{ 6.Be2 followed by 7.Nf3 is the same. } 6... Nbd7
{ We play ...Nbd7 first because we want to know if White's bishop is going on e2, Classical setup, or d3, Modern setup.   6...Nbd7  is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in our Classical setup if White plays  7.Be2  .   6...O-O  would transpose in 'What we want to avoid' where White squeezes Black with h3 + g4 ideas. }
7. Be2
{ Now we have a Classical setup @@StartBracket@@Nf3 + Be2@@EndBracket@@. In this position, the traditional move is 7...O-O. I will show you what are the main plans for Black. }
7... O-O 8. O-O { The main move for White. } 8... Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose:  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. a3
{ With 9.a3, White wants to play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@he is preparing Rb1 followed by b4@@EndBracket@@. While White will try to find counterplay on this part of the board, we will play on the kingside.  For this reason, we will use our typical regrouping plan: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7, trying to play for the ...f5 break. @@StartBracket@@PLAN A@@EndBracket@@.   Here, I will recommend you two moves:  9...Kh8!  @@StartBracket@@main recommendation@@EndBracket@@ and  9...g6  @@StartBracket@@the old main line@@EndBracket@@.   9.Ne1  Bg5  ,  White wants to relocate his knight on d3, where it can support f4 and b4. What are the consequences of this move? From f3, the knight prevented us from playing ...Bg5, but not anymore. We managed to put our bad bishop on g5, and we are ready to trade it against the c1-bishop. Next, we want to play for the ...f5 break with our typical ideas @@StartBracket@@...g6 - ...Ng7@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Kh8
{ My main recommendation. The idea is simple: We want to break with ...f5. To achieve this, we need to prepare it with ...g6 + ...Ng7. If we play 9...g6 immediately, White can play 10.Bh6.   We want White to lose a tempo. For instance, after  10.Be3  g6  11.Bh6  , then White moved his bishop twice in the opening. This is an important tempo because it avoids all the critical lines we can face with 9...g6. This is the reason why 9...Kh8! is my main recommendation. }
10. Rb1
{ A@@EndBracket@@  10.Be3  g6  11.Bh6  ,  White lost a tempo by playing Be3 first and then Bh6. You can compare with the 9.g6 line, here our king is already on h8 instead of g8 and that makes a huge difference! We move ordered him and this avoids all the critical lines.  11...Ng7  12.Qd2  Nf6  13.h3  ,  White can prevent ...Ng4 but he can't do anything against ...Ng8.  13...Ng8  ,  the bishop has to move. Our next move is ...f5.   B@@EndBracket@@  10.b4  b6  simple.  11.Ne1  g6  12.Bh6  Ng7  13.Qd2  Nd3 first was met with Bg5 to trade our bad bishop.  13...f5  ,  with no problems for Black. The knight is misplaced on e1. }
10... g6 11. Bh6 Ng7 12. Qd2 Nf6
{ We are ready to harass the bishop from g4 or g8. } 13. b4
{ 13.Ne1  Ng8  14.Be3  f5  and ...f4 is coming. } 13... b6 14. Ne1 Ng8 15. Be3
f5 { And Black has no problems. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Modern Main Line with Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7
{ We will discuss how to play with Black when White decides to put his light-square bishop on d3. }
6. Bd3
{ The modern setup @@StartBracket@@Bd3@@EndBracket@@. White keeps the choice to develop his knight on f3 or e2. We will have different ideas according to where the knight is going. Here, it is important to remember that we must play ...Nbd7 first. We are waiting for White to show his cards @@StartBracket@@where he wants to put his knight@@EndBracket@@. We don't play ...O-O yet because White has ideas like h3 followed by g4 to squeeze us. That is what we want to avoid.   6.Nf3  Nbd7  .  We play ...Nbd7 and we are waiting for White to show his cards with :   - Be2 @@StartBracket@@the Classical setup@@EndBracket@@;   - Bd3 @@StartBracket@@the Modern setup@@EndBracket@@;   - or g3 @@StartBracket@@the Fianchetto Variation we will see next@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nbd7
{ We will adapt our plan according to whether the knight comes in f3 or e2. }
7. Nf3
{ Now that the knight is on f3, we can continue with ...O-O and there is nothing to worry about.   A@@EndBracket@@  7.Nge2  ,  when the knight comes to e2, we want to take some space on the kingside with a good friend.  7...h5  ,  we push Harry! Our idea is to take space on the kingside with ...h5-h4 and to dissuade White to play Ng3.   Our typical ideas:   - We can play ...Nf8-g6: if we succeed to play ...h4, we have the ...Nh5-f4 idea.   - We can play for the ...b5 break with ...a6/...Bd7/...Rb8/...Qa5.   - We can play ...Kf8-g8. Then, our king will be safe.     B@@EndBracket@@ Next, we can build an attack on White's king if he decides to castle.  7.h3  White waits before developing his knight and would like to see us castling. But we don't want to help White, and again, we must use Harry to take some space.  7...h5  ,  we push Harry! Our ideas are always the same:   - ...h5-h4 - We want to maneuver our knight with ...Nf8;  - ...Ng6-f4 - We want to break with ...b5;   - Our king is safe on f8 and/or g8.   Notes: 8.Nge2 transposes to ourinspirational game Mamedyarov, S. - Finegold, B., 0-1, 2017. }
7... O-O
{ Our next move is ...Nh5. Next, we want to continue with our typical plan @@StartBracket@@...g6 + ...f5@@EndBracket@@. From h5, the knight is ready to jump on the f4-square if White decides to play with g3 + h4 ideas. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Fianchetto Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3
{ White plays Nf3 first and doesn't show his cards yet.   6.g3  ,  White is transparent about the fact he wants to play the Fianchetto Variation.  6...O-O   6...Na6  An interesting alternative. Black delays kingside castling because he has ideas with ...h5-h4.  7.Bg2  Nc7  .  The knight is useful on c7 to help with the ...b5 rupture. It also allows waiting to see where White develops his knight.  8.Nge2  h5  .  A strong move and the reason why we played 6...Na6. Black wants to attack the fianchetto with Harry. Next we are ready to play ...h5-h4.  9.h4  a6  We want to break through with ...b5.  10.a4  b6  An important move to remember. This prevents a5. Black is ready to play ...Rb8 followed by ...b5 next.  7.Bg2  Nbd7  8.Nge2  a6  9.a4  Ne8  and we continue with our typical regrouping plan. That is the same if White decides to play 9.O-O instead of 9.a4. }
6... Nbd7
{ We are ready to transpose in our lines against the Classical setup,  7.Be2  , or the Modern setup,  7.Bd3  . }
7. g3
{ The Fianchetto Variation. White wants to put his bishop on g2 and try to break with f4. An alternative is to play Bh3 trying to exchange his bad bishop against black's good one.   Here, I will recommend you two moves:  7...a6  , trying to go Benko style @@StartBracket@@main recommendation@@EndBracket@@ and  7...O-O  , with our typical regrouping plan on the kingside @@StartBracket@@alternative@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 { We are threatening to play ...b5 if White plays Bg2. } 8. a4
{ This move has to be played.   8.Bg2  is an inaccuracy.  8...b5  9.cxb5  axb5  and Black is already slightly better. }
8... O-O 9. Bg2 Nh5
{ Our plan is the same as with ...Ne8. But I think our knight is better placed here because we give White a chance to go wrong:  10.g4  Nf4  ,  our knight is strong and after Bxf4, we will have control over the central e5-square @@StartBracket@@...Bf6 - ...Ne5 - ...Qe7@@EndBracket@@.   If White plays  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Qxh5  Bg4  and the queen is trapped. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 1A: The Classical Variation: 9.a3 Kh8!"]
[Black "Why 9...Kh8! and not 9...g6?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3 Nbd7
{ We play ...Nbd7 first because we want to know if White's bishop is going on e2, Classical setup, or d3, Modern setup. }
7. Be2
{ Now we have a Classical setup @@StartBracket@@Nf3 + Be2@@EndBracket@@. In this position, the traditional move is 7...O-O. I will show you what are the main plans for Black. }
7... O-O 8. O-O { The main move for White. } 8... Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose :  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. a3
{ With 9.a3, White wants to play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@he is preparing Rb1 followed by b4@@EndBracket@@. While White will try to find counterplay on this part of the board, we will play on the kingside.  For this reason, we will use our typical regrouping plan: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7, trying to play for the ...f5 break. @@StartBracket@@PLAN A@@EndBracket@@. }
9... g6
{ This is the old main line. Black wants to play ...Ng7 followed by ...f5 next. This move allows White's bishop on h6.   9...Kh8  is main recommendation. It avoids all the critical lines we can face with 9...g6. White can't play Bh6. The idea is simple: We want White to lose a tempo.  10.Be3  g6  11.Bh6  ,  White moved his bishop twice in the opening. In comparison to the lines starting with 9.g6, our king is already on h8. This makes a huge difference.    11...Ng7  12.Qd2  Nf6  13.Ne1  .  Now, our king is already on h8, and we can play ...Ng8 immediately.  13...Ng8  14.Be3  f5  15.f4  .  This is the critical line when we start with 9...g6. However, there is nothing to be afraid of here because White's knight is misplaced on e1 @@StartBracket@@not d3@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Bh6 { The main move. } 10... Ng7
{ Now our plan is simple: We want to play ...Nf6-g4 to harass White's bishop. If White plays h3, then we can play ...Kh8 followed by ...Ng8. Next, we will push ...f5. }
11. Qd2 Nf6 12. Ne1
{ White is ready to exchange his bad bishop on g4 if Black plays 12...Ng4. }
12... Kh8
{ For this reason, we free the g8-square for our knight to harass the h6-bishop next.   12...Ng4  13.Bxg4  Black failed to chase the h6-bishop. }
13. Nd3 Ng8 { White has to do something about his bishop. } 14. Be3 f5 15. f4
{ This is the critical move and the reason why I recommend 9...Kh8 instead of 9...g6. The position is messy and complicated for both sides. However, White stands better here.  My main recommendation is to play 9...Kh8, but I believe this is important to be aware of the old main line.  On the one hand, this will show you how the Classical Variation has been played until now. On the other hand, it will help you understand the nuances between both moves.  This is why I decided to include lines about this variation in the next chapter @@StartBracket@@as an alternative@@EndBracket@@. }
*

