1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3
{ 6.Be2 followed by 7.Nf3 is the same. } 6... Nbd7
{ We play ...Nbd7 first because we want to know if White's bishop is going on e2, Classical setup, or d3, Modern setup. }
7. Be2
{ Now we have a Classical setup @@StartBracket@@Nf3 + Be2@@EndBracket@@. In this position, the traditional move is 7...O-O. I will show you what are the main plans for Black. }
7... O-O 8. O-O { The main move for White. } 8... Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose :  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. a3
{ With 9.a3, White wants to play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@he is preparing Rb1 followed by b4@@EndBracket@@. While White will try to find counterplay on this part of the board, we will play on the kingside.  For this reason, we will use our typical regrouping plan: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7, trying to play for the ...f5 break. @@StartBracket@@PLAN A@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Kh8
{ My main recommendation. The idea is simple: We want to break with ...f5. To achieve this, we need to prepare it with ...g6 + ...Ng7. If we play 9...g6 immediately, White can play 10.Bh6.   We want White to lose a tempo. For instance, after  10.Be3  g6  11.Bh6  , then White moved his bishop twice in the opening. This is an important tempo because it avoids all the critical lines we can face with 9...g6. This is the reason why 9...Kh8! is my main recommendation. }
10. Be3 g6 11. Bh6
{ White lost a tempo by playing Be3 first and then Bh6. You can compare with the 9...g6 line − here our king is already on h8 instead of g8 and that makes a huge difference!  We move ordered White and this avoids all the critical lines. }
11... Ng7 12. Qd2 Nf6 13. h3
{ White can prevent ...Ng4 but he can't do anything against ...Ng8. } 13... Ng8
14. Bg5 f5 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. b4 b6 17. Rfd1 f4
{ And Black is slightly better and will grab the initiative with our typical plan from the King's Indian Defense.  This is ourmodel game Baluta, Constantin  (2295)  - Bricard, Emmanuel  (2450)  , 0-1, 1998. }
