{ With 9.a3, White wants to play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@he is preparing Rb1 followed by b4@@EndBracket@@. While White will try to find counterplay on this part of the board, we will play on the kingside.  For this reason, we will use our typical regrouping plan: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7, trying to play for the ...f5 break. @@StartBracket@@PLAN A@@EndBracket@@. }
9... g6
{ This is the old main line. Black wants to play ...Ng7 followed by ...f5 next. }
10. Bh6 { The main move. } 10... Ng7
{ Now our plan is simple: We want to play ...Nf6-g4 to harass White's bishop. If White plays h3, then we can play ...Kh8 followed by ...Ng8. Next, we will push ...f5. }
11. Qd2 Nf6 12. Ne1 { This move prevents us to play ...Ng4. } 12... Kh8
{ ...Ng8 is coming. } 13. Nd3 Ng8 14. Be3 f5 { The threat is ...f5-f4. } 15. f4
{ The critical move. This position is difficult for both sides, and Black has to choose between ...exf4 and ...fxe4.   The good move is  15...fxe4!  the only one game in my database, while I found 12 games where Black chose the wrong path with  15...exf4?  Our goal is to exchange pieces to simplify the game. We can avoid those lines by playing 9...Kh8!, that is why 9...g6 is given as an alternative in the course. }
15... fxe4 16. Nxe4 Bf5
{ We want to harass the strong knight as soon as possible. } 17. Nc3 exf4 18.
Nxf4 { White is threatening g4 is coming and we should prevent it. } 18... Qd7
{ 18...g5  is also possible but the positions are really complicated for both sides. }
19. h3
{ g4 is coming again but this time we are not afraid and we move forward. }
19... Nf6 20. g4 { Black has an efficient antidote. } 20... Ne4 21. Nxe4 Bxe4
22. Bd3 Bxd3 23. Qxd3 Bf6 { The game is equal but I prefer our king's safety. }
*

