1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O
Ne8 9. a3 Kh8
{ Next, you will find three models games where White played 9.a3 and where Black decided to play 9...Kh8!  Baluta, Constantin - Bricard, Emmanuel
Kielhorn, Sebastian - Hauschild, Andreas
Cordes, Hans Joerg - Ghinda, Mihail }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 1: Model Games"]
[Black "Baluta, Constantin (2295) vs. Bricard, Emmanuel (2450)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2
{ The Classical setup @@StartBracket@@Nf3 + Be2@@EndBracket@@. } 7... Nbd7 8.
O-O Ne8
{ Our typical move. Now we wait for White to move before we choose between PLAN A or PLAN B. }
9. a3
{ With 9.a3, White wants to play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@he is preparing Rb1 followed by b4@@EndBracket@@. While White will try to find counterplay on this part of the board, we will play on the kingside.  For this reason, we will use our typical regrouping plan: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7, trying to play for the ...f5 break. @@StartBracket@@PLAN A@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Kh8
{ My main recommendation. The idea is simple: We want to break with ...f5. To achieve this, we need to prepare it with ...g6 + ...Ng7. If we play 9...g6 immediately, White can play 10.Bh6.   We want White to lose a tempo. For instance, after  10.Be3  g6  11.Bh6  , then White moved his bishop twice in the opening. This is an important tempo because it avoids all the critical lines we can face with 9...g6. This is the reason why 9...Kh8! is my main recommendation. }
10. Be3 g6 11. Qd2 Ng7 12. Bh6
{ White lost a tempo because he played Be3 + Bh6 instead of Bh6 directly. This makes a huge difference. }
12... Nf6 13. h3 { This prevents ...Ng4 but not ...Ng8. } 13... Ng8
{ White has to make a choice about his bishop. } 14. Bg5 f5
{ 14...f6  first with the same idea was best. But  14...f5  is fine. } 15. Bxe7
Qxe7 16. b4 b6 { Typical. } 17. Rfd1
{ White should have played  17.Qg5  to propose the exchange of the queens. }
17... f4
{ Now Black closes the position and is ready to build an attack against White's king in a typical KID fashion. }
18. Ne1 g5 19. Bg4
{ A blunder. The c8-bishop is often strong in this kind of position. White thought it would be a nice idea to exchange it. }
19... Bxg4 20. hxg4 h5
{ Harry five! A strong move that doesn't give a chance for White to stabilize the position. }
21. gxh5 g4 22. f3 Nxh5 23. bxc5
{ 23.fxg4  is well met by  23...Ng3  and White's position is undefendable. }
23... bxc5 24. Kf2 { White's king tries to run but it is already too late. }
24... Ng3 { No escape square for you sir. } 25. Ne2
{ Trying to exchange the knight on g3 but now comes: } 25... Nxe4+
{ White is forced to take the 'free' knight. } 26. fxe4 Qh4+ 27. g3
{ 27.Kf1  loses to  27...f3  and the king has no chance at all. } 27... Qh2+
28. Ng2 fxg3+
{ White resigns.  A beautiful game by Black. This game is instructive to understand how dangerous the Czech Benoni can be. Don't forget about this KID's-like plan because you will win a lot of games with it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 1: Model Games"]
[Black "Kielhorn, Sebastian vs. Hauschild, Andreas"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2
{ The Classical setup @@StartBracket@@Nf3 + Be2@@EndBracket@@. } 7... Ne8
{ Our typical move. Now we wait for White to move before we choose between PLAN A or PLAN B. }
8. O-O Nd7 9. a3
{ With 9.a3, White wants to play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@he is preparing Rb1 followed by b4@@EndBracket@@. While White will try to find counterplay on this part of the board, we will play on the kingside.  For this reason, we will use our typical regrouping plan: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7, trying to play for the ...f5 break. @@StartBracket@@PLAN A@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Kh8
{ My main recommendation. The idea is simple: We want to break with ...f5. To achieve this, we need to prepare it with ...g6 + ...Ng7. If we play 9...g6 immediately, White can play 10.Bh6.   We want White to lose a tempo. For instance, after  10.Be3  g6  11.Bh6  , then White moved his bishop twice in the opening. This is an important tempo because it avoids all the critical lines we can face with 9...g6. This is the reason why 9...Kh8! is my main recommendation. }
10. b4 b6 { Typical. } 11. h3
{ This move is not useful and will cost White the game. It was better to develop the queen or the bishop on c1. }
11... Ndf6 12. Bg5 Ng8
{ Do you want to trade my bad bishop against your good one? } 13. Be3 g6
{ Our usual ideas again. } 14. Nd2 Bg5 15. f4
{ A mistake because it allows Black to exchange his bad bishop and free the e5-square for his pieces. }
15... exf4 16. Bxf4 Bxf4 17. Rxf4 Bxh3 { What was the point of h3? } 18. g3
{ 18.gxh3  Qg5+  19.Rg4  Qe3+  20.Kh2  Qxc3  .  Geometry! } 18... Bd7 19. Kg2
Qe7 20. Rh4 f5
{ Black wants to open the f-file and build an attack against White's king. }
21. Nf3 g5 22. Rh2 fxe4 23. Nxe4 Rxf3
{ Boom!   23...Qxe4  Black's point was that ...Qxe4 could be met with  24.Bd3  .  However, Black is still winning after the nice  24...Bf5  25.Bxe4  Bxe4  26.Kg1  Rxf3  and the three pieces are enough for the queen but White could have tried to swindle the game. That is why the move played in the game is better. }
24. Kxf3 { 24.Bxf3  g4 } 24... g4+ 25. Ke3 Nef6 { Black exploits the pin. } 26.
Bd3 Nxe4 27. Bxe4 { Black will win the bishop. } 27... Bf5 28. Qc2 Re8 29. Qb2+
Nf6 30. Kd2 Bxe4 31. Re1 Qg7 { The knight is unpinned. } 32. Rhe2 Qg5+ 33. Kc3
Qe5+ 34. Kb3 Qxb2+ 35. Kxb2 Kg7 36. Kc3 Kf7 { Now the bishop is free. } 37.
bxc5 bxc5
{ Black's plan is simple:    Exchange a rook if possible.  Attack the weak g3-pawn.  Push Harry and Garry to make a new queen. }
38. Rb2 Re7 39. Rb8 Nh5 40. Rd8 Nxg3 { Step 1. } 41. Rxd6 Bf5 42. Rxe7+
{ Step 2. } 42... Kxe7 43. Ra6 Ne4+ 44. Kd3 g3 { Step 3. } 45. Rxa7+ Bd7 46.
Rb7 Nd6 47. Rb2 h5 48. Rc2
{ White resigns. There is nothing to do against Harry and Garry. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 1: Model Games"]
[Black "Cordes, Hans Joerg vs. Ghinda, Mihail Viorel"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Nbd7 6. Be2 Be7 7. Nf3
{ The Classical setup @@StartBracket@@Nf3 + Be2 followed by O-O@@EndBracket@@. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose:  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. a3
{ With 9.a3, White wants to play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@he is preparing Rb1 followed by b4@@EndBracket@@. While White will try to find counterplay on this part of the board, we will play on the kingside.  For this reason, we will use our typical regrouping plan: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7, trying to play for the ...f5 break. @@StartBracket@@PLAN A@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Kh8
{ My main recommendation. The idea is simple: We want to break with ...f5. To achieve this, we need to prepare it with ...g6 + ...Ng7. If we play 9...g6 immediately, White can play 10.Bh6.   We want White to lose a tempo. For instance, after  10.Be3  g6  11.Bh6  , then White moved his bishop twice in the opening. This is an important tempo because it avoids all the critical lines we can face with 9...g6. This is the reason why 9...Kh8! is my main recommendation. }
10. Bd2 g6 11. Qc1 Ng7 { ...f5 is coming. } 12. Ne1 f5
{ Black succeeds to break through without difficulty. } 13. exf5 gxf5
{ Our typical recapture. The e4-square is under control, and the g-file is opened. }
14. f4 e4 15. g4 { This is weakening. } 15... fxg4 16. Nxe4 Nf6 17. Ng5
{ 17.Ng3  was best. This just loses a pawn. } 17... h6 18. Ne6 Bxe6 19. dxe6
Nxe6 20. Bc3 d5 { 20...Nd4  was best but  20...d5  is correct. } 21. cxd5 Nd4
{ The d5-pawn is under attack. } 22. Bxd4 cxd4
{ Black is ready to put all of his pieces on good squares. } 23. Nd3 Rc8 24.
Qe1 Nxd5 25. Ne5 Ne3 { The knight is a monster on d3. } 26. Bd3
{ Black is winning but has to be careful until the end. } 26... Kg7
{ 26...Nxf1  27.Qe4  and now Black is lost. } 27. Nxg4 Nxg4 28. Qe4 Rg8
{ Now the knight is indirectly protected and the king is ready to escape. } 29.
Rf3 Nf6 30. Rg3+ Kf7 31. Qxb7 Qd5
{ Black wants to trade pieces to realize his material advantage. } 32. Bg6+
Rxg6 33. Qxc8 d3 { There is nothing to do against ...Bc5+. White resigns. } *

