[White "Theory 1: Model Games"]
[Black "Sarno, Spartaco vs. Seirawan, Yasser"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Be2 Nbd7 7. Nf3
{ The Classical setup @@StartBracket@@Nf3 + Be2 followed by O-O@@EndBracket@@. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose:  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. a3
{ With 9.a3, White wants to play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@he is preparing Rb1 followed by b4@@EndBracket@@. While White will try to find counterplay on this part of the board, we will play on the kingside.  For this reason, we will use our typical regrouping plan: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7, trying to play for the ...f5 break. @@StartBracket@@PLAN A@@EndBracket@@. }
9... g6 { The old main line. } 10. b4 b6
{ Again a typical move. In the case of bxc5, we can recapture ...bxc5, and it will be difficult for White to penetrate on the queenside. }
11. bxc5 bxc5 12. Rb1
{ It is very hard to find how White can infiltrate on the queenside. } 12... f5
{ We break through with Freddy! } 13. Qa4 Nb6 14. Qc2 f4
{ Black closes the position. Now, he is ready to use our typical plan from the King's Indian Defense. }
15. Ne1 Nf6 16. Bd2 Rf7 { ...Kh8 followed by ...Rg8 was also fine. } 17. f3 h5
{ Harry, Garry, and Freddy join the party together! } 18. Na4 Nbd7 19. Nd3 g5
20. Nf2 Rg7 21. h3 Nf8
{ Black can break with ...g4 next. The knight from f8 is also ready to join the attack. }
22. Rb3 g4 { Black open lines on the White's king. } 23. fxg4 hxg4 24. Bxg4
Nxg4 25. Nxg4 Bxg4 26. hxg4 { White's position is lost. } 26... Qd7 27. Rd3
Qxg4 28. Be1 { 28.Rf2  Bh4 } 28... Nh7 { Bringing more pieces in the attack. }
29. Nc3 Ng5 30. Qe2
{ The exchange of the queens will not help White because of all the pawn weaknesses. }
30... Qxe2 31. Nxe2 Nxe4 { The game is over. } 32. Rb3 Rf8
{ Everyone joins the party. } 33. Rb7 f3 34. Ng3 Nxg3 35. Bxg3 e4
{ 35...Rxg3  was best. The move played in the game is strong enough and avoids any counterplay.  36.Rxe7  Rxg2+  37.Kh1  Rg4  . }
36. Rf2 { 36.Kh2  Rf5  37.Rf2  Rf6  38.gxf3  exf3  and ...Rh6 is coming. }
36... e3 { White resigns. } 37. Rxf3 Rxf3 38. gxf3 Rxg3+ 39. Kf1 Bg5
{ A beautiful game by one of our Czech Benoni heroes. This game is instructive to show how much danger White can face if he is too passive. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 1: Model Games"]
[Black "Schmidt, Wlodzimierz vs. Podzielny, Karl Heinz"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Be2 O-O 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. O-O
Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose:  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. a3
{ With 9.a3, White wants to play on the queenside @@StartBracket@@he is preparing Rb1 followed by b4@@EndBracket@@. While White will try to find counterplay on this part of the board, we will play on the kingside.  For this reason, we will use our typical regrouping plan: ...g6 followed by ...Ng7, trying to play for the ...f5 break. @@StartBracket@@PLAN A@@EndBracket@@. }
9... g6 { The old main line. } 10. Bh6
{ A good move, but it doesn't prevent our plan! } 10... Ng7
{ White is welcome if he wants to trade his good bishop. } 11. Qd2
{ 11.Ne1  is a natural move to relocate the knight but a mistake because it allows us to get rid of White's good bishop.  11...Bg5  . After  12.Bxg5  Qxg5  or Bxg7/...Kxg7, Black has no problems. }
11... Nf6
{ A typical maneuver. We want to play ...Kh8 followed by ...Ng8 to harass White's bishop. }
12. Ne1 Kh8 13. Nd3 Ng8 14. Be3 f5 { Now we are ready to break through. } 15.
f4
{ The only move. White is better, but the game is complicated. 15...exf4 was played in this game by Black but also in a dozen of games. However, 15...fxe4 is best! @@StartBracket@@and my recommendation for our lines with the alternative 9...g6@@EndBracket@@.   15.f3  f4  16.Bf2  ,  with our typical attacking's plan from the King's Indian Defense. }
15... exf4
{ White stands better but the position is complicated.   15...fxe4  was best and my recommendation in the theory section. }
16. Bxf4 g5 { Black wants chaos. } 17. Be3 Bf6
{ Activating the bishop.   17...f4  ,  this natural move helps White with his plan to break through with e5!  18.Bf2  b6  19.Rae1  Ba6  20.b3  Bf6  21.e5  . }
18. e5 { A natural move but a mistake, b4 was best.  18.b4  fxe4  . } 18...
dxe5 19. Nxc5 b6 20. Nb3 Re8 21. c5
{ Now, Black takes the initiative.   21.Qc2  e4 } 21... f4 22. Bf2 e4 23. Bd4
e3 24. Qd1 bxc5 25. Nxc5 { Mistake. Bxc5 was best. } 25... Nf5 26. Bxf6+ Nxf6
{ The two black knights are back in the game now. } 27. Qd3 Qe7 28. b4 Qe5 29.
Rad1 Nd6
{ This move is a blunder. Black didn't want to allow any counterplay based on the d-pawn.  29.g4  was best. }
30. Qd4 Bg4 { Black wants to trade pieces and use his kingside pawn majority. }
31. Bxg4 Nxg4 { Those pawns are powerful. } 32. Ne6
{ The e6-square looks juicy for the knight. But in reality, White's knight is doing nothing on e6 and can't attack alone.  Indeed, White's queen is unable to join the knight to build an attack. Here, the queens have to be exchanged on e5 at some point. Trying to avoid the queens' trade is a mistake.   For instance  32...Rac8  33.Qd3  f3  and White is in trouble. }
32... Rac8 { Black takes control of the c-file. } 33. Ne2 Rc2
{ Black's rook seizes the 2nd rank. } 34. Qxe5+
{ As explained, this was unavoidable. } 34... Nxe5
{ Black is ready to use his kingside pawn majority. } 35. N2d4 Rb2 36. Rb1 Rd2
37. Rfd1 Ne4 { Black wants to trade rooks on his own terms. } 38. Rxd2 exd2
{ This pawn is a killer. } 39. Rd1 Nc4 { ...Nc3 is threatened. } 40. Nf3
{ Preventing ...Nc3. } 40... g4 { But Garry is here. White resigns. } *

