[Black "El Debs, Felipe vs. Segal, Alexandru Sorin"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Be2
{ The Classical setup @@StartBracket@@Nf3 + Be2@@EndBracket@@. } 7... O-O 8.
O-O Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose:  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. Ne1
{ White wants to relocate his knight on d3, where it can support f4 and b4. What are the consequences of this move? From f3, the knight prevented us from playing ...Bg5, but not anymore. }
9... a6 { 9...Bg5  is best and my recommendation. } 10. a3 Bg5
{ Black would be happy to trade his bad bishop against White's good bishop. Now, the bad bishop is at least 'active/useful' for the time being. }
11. Nd3 g6
{ Black is preparing our typical regrouping plan @@StartBracket@@...Ng7 to breakthrough with ...f5 at the right moment@@EndBracket@@. }
12. b4 b6 13. Rb1 Ng7 14. bxc5 bxc5 15. f4
{ This move is premature. Black is ready to take control over the e5-square.   15.Bxg5  Qxg5 }
15... exf4 16. Bxf4 Bxf4 17. Rxf4 Qe7
{ We are ready to jump on e5 with our knight and take the control of the game. }
18. Bg4 { 18.Qd2  Ra7 } 18... Ne5
{ 18...f5  is a good alternative.  19.exf5  Qe3+  20.Rf2  Nf6  21.Bh3  Bxf5  22.Bxf5  Nxf5  23.Qf3  Qd4  .  Our pieces are very active and the c4-pawn will fall. }
19. Bxc8
{ White succeeds in trading his bad bishop for Black's good one. However, the control over the central squares @@StartBracket@@and the dark squares@@EndBracket@@ is more important here. }
19... Raxc8 20. Nxe5 Qxe5 21. Rf3 f5
{ Black breaks through with Freddy! However,  21...Rb8  was more precise. } 22.
exf5 Rxf5 23. Rxf5 { Mistake.  23.Qd2  was best. } 23... Nxf5 24. Qe2 Qd4+ 25.
Kh1 Rf8
{ 25...Kf8  preparing ...Re8 and avoiding any check on e6 was best. But Black was afraid about counterplay. }
26. Nd1 { Blunder.  26.Ne4  was best. } 26... Ng7 27. g3
{ Again a mistake. Now there are new weaknesses to exploit. } 27... Re8
{ The game is lost. } 28. Qc2 Re1+ 29. Kg2 Qg1+ 30. Kh3 Qf1+ 31. Kh4 Nf5+ 32.
Kg5 Re8 { 32...Re5  was more precise. } 33. Nf2 Qg2 34. Rb7 Qxh2 35. Ng4 Qh5+
{ White resigns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 1: Model Games"]
[Black "Hegeler, Frank vs. Jansa, Vlastimil"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Be2 O-O 7. Nf3 Ne8 8. O-O
Nd7 9. Ne1
{ White wants to relocate his knight on d3, where it can support f4 and b4. What are the consequences of this move? From f3, the knight prevented us from playing ...Bg5, but not anymore. }
9... Bg5
{ Black managed to put his bad bishop on g5, and he is ready to trade it against the c1-bishop. Next, he wants to play for the ...f5 break with our typical ideas ...g6, ...Ng7. }
10. Nd3
{ Our bishop is well placed on g5 and if possible we would like White to take on g5 to develop our queen. Now we achieved our PLAN B, we don't forget that we want to push Freddy to break through. }
10... g6 11. g3
{ Black wanted White to take on g5. However, he understands g3 is played with the intention to push f4. }
11... Bxc1 { Blach has no bad bishop anymore. } 12. Qxc1 Qe7 13. f4 exf4 14.
gxf4 Ng7 15. Qe3 Nf5
{ Black takes advantage of the pinned queen to jump on the juicy d4-square. }
16. Qf2 Nd4 17. Rae1 Nb6 18. e5 Bf5
{ 18...Nxc4  was not working because of  19.Nxc5  19...Nxe2+  20.Qxe2  20...dxc5  21.Qxc4  . }
19. b3 a5 20. Qg3 a4 21. Bd1 axb3 22. axb3 Ra1 23. Kh1 Rfa8 24. Ne4
{ The mistake of the game. Now comes  24.Bg4  .  Trying to simplify the game was the correct continuation. }
24... Rxd1 25. Nf6+
{ 25.Nxd6  was the best alternative but the position is still lost for White.  25...Rxe1  26.Nxe1  Ra3  . }
25... Qxf6 26. exf6 Rxd3
{ Three pieces for the queen is enough to win the game! } 27. Re3 Be4+ 28. Rxe4
{ 28.Kg1  Ne2+  29.Rxe2  Rxg3+ } 28... Rxg3 29. hxg3 Nd7
{ Black is better, but he needs to eliminate f6 quickly to avoid any problems with Rfe1 followed by Ree8+. }
30. Re7 Nxf6 31. Rxb7 Ra2
{ The king is cut off, and the knights are ready to join the party. } 32. b4
Ng4 { White resigns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 1: Model Games"]
[Black "Soldatkin, Alexandr vs. Bulmaga, Irina"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O
Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose:  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. Ne1 { What to do? } 9... Bg5
{ Of course, Black takes the opportunity to trade his bad bishop. } 10. Nd3
Bxc1 11. Qxc1 Qe7
{ Now, f4 is well met by ...exf4 with good control over the e5-square. } 12.
Qe3 a6 { A useful move to prepare the ...b5 break in the future. } 13. a4 g6
14. f4 { This is premature and gives Black control over the e5-square. } 14...
exf4 15. Qxf4 Ng7 16. Rae1 f6 17. Qd2 Ne5 18. Nxe5 fxe5 19. Rxf8+ Qxf8 20. Qg5
Bd7 21. Bg4 { White succeed in exchanging his bad bishop. } 21... Bxg4 22. Qxg4
Qe7 23. Rf1 Rf8 24. Rxf8+ Kxf8
{ The position is equal. In this kind of position, it is important to do your best to stay active and not fall into passivity. In the game, White started to err, and we will see the result. }
25. Qc8+ Ne8 26. a5 Kg7
{ Freeing the knight, which is now ready to jump on f6 and reach White's king. }
27. Na4 Nf6 { Attacking the e4-pawn. } 28. Nc3
{ White's knight is restricted to the protection of the e4-pawn. The game is still equal, but it's already a good point for Black. }
28... h5
{ This move is multi-purpose: it takes space on the kingside and it gives a safe square @@StartBracket@@h6@@EndBracket@@ for Black's king. }
29. h3 h4
{ Taking more space. Now the idea ...Nh5-g3 and playing for an attack comes to mind. }
30. Kf1 Nh5 31. Ke1
{ 31.Qg4  is necessary. The queen isn't doing anything on c8 and needs to help with the protection of White's king. }
31... Nf4 32. Kd2 Nxg2
{ 32...Qg5  was stronger.  33.Qg4  Qxg4  34.hxg4  Nxg2  Harry will help to divert White's king. And the knight will eat all the weak pawns.  35.Ke2  h3  36.Kf3  Ne3  37.Kxe3  h2  and if @@StartFEN@@8/1p4k1/p2p2p1/P1pPp3/2P1P1P1/2N1nK1p/1P6/8 w - - 2 37@@EndFEN@@  37.Kg3  Nxc4  38.Kxh3  . }
33. Kc2 { 33.Qg4  was the last chance.  33...Nf4  . } 33... Ne3+ 34. Kb3 Kh7
35. Ne2 Kg7 36. Ng1 Qf7 37. Qd8 Qf2 { The knight is lost and so is the game. }
38. Ne2 Qxe2 39. Qe7+ Kh6 40. Qxh4+ Qh5 41. Qd8 Qd1+ 42. Ka2 Qa4+ 43. Kb1 Qc2+
44. Ka2 Qxc4+ 45. Kb1 Qxe4+ 46. Ka2 Qxd5+ 47. Kb1 Qd3+ 48. Ka2 Qc4+ 49. Kb1
Qc2+ 50. Ka2 Nf5 51. Qh8+ Kg5 52. Qd8+ Kf4 53. h4 Qg2
{ White resigns. This game is instructive to show how you need to fight for activity until the end of the game if you don't want to end like White in this game. }
