[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 1: Model Games"]
[Black "Comp Hiarcs,  vs. Seirawan, Yasser"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Be2 O-O 8. Bd2
{ White didn't castle as expected. When this happens to you, there is no reason to panic. The plans are still here to help you. }
8... Ne8
{ Black goes for our typical regrouping plan.  8...Nh5  ,  preparing our typical regrouping plan was also fine. }
9. O-O g6 10. Bh6 Ng7 11. Qd2 Nf6 { Black wants to get rid of the h6-bishop. }
12. h3 { The g4-square is now under control. } 12... Kh8
{ The knight is ready to harass the bishop from g8. } 13. a3 Ng8 14. b4 Nxh6
15. Qxh6 b6 { Typical. } 16. h4 f6 17. Bd1 a6 18. Ba4 Ra7
{ The rook is ready to come to g7 in the future. } 19. bxc5 bxc5 20. Rfe1 Nh5
21. Bc6 Rg8 { Black would like to chase the queen from h6. } 22. Qd2 f5
{ Time to break through. } 23. Ng5 Bxg5 24. Qxg5 Qf8
{ Black doesn't want to trade queens. ...h6 to chase the White's queen is coming. }
25. exf5 h6 26. Qg4 Nf6 27. Qf3 gxf5
{ Our typical recapture. Now Black has control over the e4-square and the rook is ready to lift on g7. }
28. Ne2 Rag7 29. Kh1 f4 30. Rg1 Bg4 31. Qd3 Nh5
{ All the black pieces are working together. Only the queen needs to be mobilized now; ...Qf6-h4 is unstoppable. }
32. Nxf4 { White understands he is lost and tries to complicate the matters. }
32... exf4 33. Qc3 { This prevents ...Qf6 but not ...Qe7! } 33... Qe7 34. g3
{ The h4-pawn is defended at the cost of new weaknesses. } 34... Qe2
{ There are too many weaknesses around White's king. White resigns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 1: Model Games"]
[Black "Nielsen, Peter Heine (2651) vs. Carlsen, Magnus (2690)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Be2 Nbd7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. O-O
Ne8
{ Here, it is important to know that we play 8...Ne8, but it is more important to know why we play 8...Ne8!  This move is multi-purpose:  - We want to break with ...f5. For this reason, we are going to fianchetto our knight on g7 after ...g6, and the knight will help to achieve our plan.  PLAN A   - The knight was obstructing our bad bishop on e7. Now, the path to g5 is free, and we will try to exchange our bad bishop on g5 if possible.  PLAN B   In this position, White has two main moves:  9.a3  and  9.Ne1  . }
9. Rb1
{ White played  9.Rb1  instead of  9.a3  or  9.Ne1  .   There is no reason to panic. With 9.Rb1, White wants to play on the queenside with a3-b4. That's the same as with 9.a3. And what is our plan against 9.a3? }
9... g6 { We want to play on the kingside! PLAN A } 10. Ne1
{ What are the consequences of this move? } 10... Bg5
{ The knight is not controlling g5 anymore and we can trade our bad bishop! }
11. Nd3 Bxc1 12. Qxc1 Qe7
{ The queen is ready to control the e5-square in the case of f4, ...exf4. } 13.
f4 exf4 14. Qxf4 f6 { This move helps to control the e5-square. } 15. Rf2 Ne5
16. Nxe5 dxe5
{ 16...fxe5  was also possible.  Magnus wanted to free the d6-square for his knight where it can be a good blockader, attacking e4 and c4 but also helping to push ...f5 or ...b5! }
17. Qe3 b6 18. Rbf1 Bd7
{ 18...Nd6  was met with  19.Nb5  .  Now the knight is ready to jump on d6. }
19. h4 Nd6 { This is an excellent place for the knight. } 20. h5 f5
{ Time to break through. } 21. g3 { Preventing ...f4. } 21... gxh5
{ 21...Rae8  keeping the tension, was best. } 22. Bd3 fxe4 23. Nxe4 Nxe4 24.
Bxe4 Rxf2 25. Rxf2 Rf8 26. d6 Qg7 27. Bd5+ Kh8 28. Rxf8+ Qxf8 29. Qg5 h6 30.
Qg6 Qg7 31. Qxh5
{ After some simplifications, White made the fatal mistake and didn't recover. }
31... Qxg3+ 32. Kh1 Qe1+ 33. Kg2 Qd2+ 34. Kh1 Qc1+ 35. Kh2 Qf4+ 36. Kh1 Kg7 37.
Bg2 Qc1+ 38. Kh2 Qf4+ 39. Kh1 e4 40. Bh3 Qc1+ 41. Kh2 Qxb2+ 42. Bg2 Qf6 43.
Bxe4 Qf4+
{ White resigns. Nice to see that even our World Champion used the Czech Benoni with success! }
*

[Event "?"]
