[White "Theory 2A: Modern Main Line (Nf3 + Bd3)"]
[Black "Nf3 + Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3 Nbd7
{ We play ...Nbd7 first because we want to know if White's bishop is going on e2, Classical setup, or d3, Modern setup.   6...Nbd7  is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in our Classical setup if White plays  7.Be2  .   6...O-O  would transpose in 'What we want to avoid' where White squeezes Black with h3 + g4 ideas. }
7. Bd3 O-O
{ Now we can castle, and we are not afraid of h3 + g4 ideas. White has two main moves here: 8.h3 and 8.O-O. }
8. h3 { White wants to play g4 next. But here, we can play: } 8... Nh5
{ The knight is ready to jump on the f4-square.  ...Nh5 is possible here for two reasons:  White's light-squared bishop is on d3 @@StartBracket@@not f1@@EndBracket@@. Black's b8-knight is developed on d7.   9.Nxe5  is not possible because  9...Nxe5  10.Qxh5  Nxd3+  . }
9. Ne2 { A good move. White prevents us to jump on the f4-square. } 9... g6
{ g4 is coming and we can't jump on f4. For this reason, our usual plan will help you to find a square for our knight on g7. }
10. g4 { The critical line. We have to be careful here. } 10... Ng7 11. Bh6 Nf6
{ And we can continue with our typical plan. } 12. g5
{ This is tempting, but it doesn't work at all. Black is not obliged to move backward and can jump on the h5-square, which is not protected anymore. }
12... Nfh5
{ From h5, the knight gives more control to the f4-square. Black is ready to continue with his plan to break on both sides of the board. For instance, the game could continue: }
13. Qd2 { 13.a4  f6  and Black is fine. } 13... a6 14. a4 f5
{ Time to breakthrough. Black threatens to play ...fxe4 followed by ...Bf5. }
15. gxf6 { The only way to capture.  15.exf5  Bxf5  and Black is much better. }
15... Bxf6
{ And Black is fine.  15...Rxf6  is an alternative.   The g-file is opened and White would like to undermine our structure with h4-h5. But this is not possible because of our h5-knight! }
