[Black "Nf3 + Bd3 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3 Nbd7
{ We play ...Nbd7 first because we want to know if White's bishop is going on e2, Classical setup, or d3, Modern setup.   6...Nbd7  is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in our Classical setup if White plays  7.Be2  .   6...O-O  would transpose in 'What we want to avoid' where White squeezes Black with h3 + g4 ideas. }
7. Bd3 O-O
{ Now we can castle, and we are not afraid of h3 + g4 ideas. White has two main moves here: 8.h3 and 8.O-O. }
8. O-O Nh5
{ We just need to follow our typical plan. We will have a strong attack against White's king. }
9. g3
{ White controls the important f4-square.   After our ...f5 breakthrough, we would like to push ...f5-f4 to close the position and use our typical plan from the King's Indian Defense. 9.g3 prevents this strong plan.  In ourmodel game Akhmadeev, Vadim  (2439)  vs. Khismatullin, Denis  (2584)  , 0-1, White played 9.Re1 instead of 9.g3.   Because the f4-square was not controlled enough by White, Black managed to close the position with ...f5-f4. Then, he used our typical plan from the King's Indian Defense with success. }
9... g6 10. Ne1 Ng7 { ...f5 will come next. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 2B: Modern Main Line (Bd3 + Nge2)"]
[Black "Bd3 + Nge2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3
{ White keeps the possibility to play 7.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@this transposes to our Nf3 + Bd3 lines@@EndBracket@@  or Nge2  @@StartBracket@@what we are going to study here@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nbd7
{ This is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in the Modern setup where White plays Nf3 + Bd3.   6...O-O  would invite White to play h3-g4 ideas. We want to see where White decides to put his g1-knight before we decide to castle or not. }
7. Nge2 h5
{ We push Harry! Our idea is to take space on the kingside with ...h5-h4 and to dissuade White to play Ng3.  Our typical ideas:   We can play ...Nf8-g6: if we succeed to play ...h4, we have the ...Nh5-f4 idea.  We can play for the ...b5 break with ...a6/...Bd7/...Rb8/...Qa5.  We can play ...Kf8-g8. Then, our king will be in safety. Next, we can build an attack on White's king if he decides to castle. }
8. h4 { The critical move. } 8... Nf8 9. f3 Ng6 10. g3
{ The critical line: White doesn't want us to play on the kingside. White stands better, but I believe this position is easier to play for Black in practical play.  The kingside is locked. Next, we want to play for the ...b5 break @@StartBracket@@...Bd7, ...a6, ...Rb8@@EndBracket@@. Our king will be safe on g8. }
10... Bd7
{ Ourmodel game for this line is : Gozzoli, Y.  2583  - Finegold, B., 0-1, 2017.  Next, we can continue with ...a6-...Rb8-...b5 and put our king into safety with ...Kf8-g8. In general, we prefer to avoid castling kingside.  Our h8-rook is already active and is better placed on h8 than f8.   An interesting idea to keep in mind is the rover ...Rh6-g6 or ...Rh6-f6. We have already met this idea in ourinspirational game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 2B: Modern Main Line (Bd3 + Nge2)"]
[Black "Bd3 + Nge2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3
{ White keeps the possibility to play 7.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@this transposes to our Nf3 + Bd3 lines@@EndBracket@@  or Nge2  @@StartBracket@@what we are going to study here@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nbd7
{ This is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in the Modern setup where White plays Nf3 + Bd3.   6...O-O  would invite White to play h3-g4 ideas. We want to see where White decides to put his g1-knight before we decide to castle or not. }
7. Nge2 h5
{ We push Harry! Our idea is to take space on the kingside with ...h5-h4 and to dissuade White to play Ng3.  Our typical ideas:   We can play ...Nf8-g6: if we succeed to play ...h4, we have the ...Nh5-f4 idea.  We can play for the ...b5 break with ...a6/...Bd7/...Rb8/...Qa5.  We can play ...Kf8-g8. Then, our king will be in safety. Next, we can build an attack on White's king if he decides to castle. }
8. h4 { The critical move. } 8... Nf8 9. Ng3 Ng4
{ The idea of 9...Ng4 is simple: we want to win the h4-pawn next. The computer is not afraid of this move and can explain why with a thousand variations. But practically, I think humans can feel they have already been tricked in the opening. }
10. Nf5 Bxf5 11. exf5 Bxh4 12. Ne4 Be7
{ We are ready to:    come back on f6 if White plays f3 @@StartBracket@@then there is no x-ray by the queen against our harry@@EndBracket@@; exchange the strong e4-knight. 
  We will prepare our ...b5 breakthrough next.  Be careful about ideas like Qxg4, ...hxg4, Rxh8. We are not against this sacrifice, but we must be aware of this possibility and not be surprised by it. For instance, the game could continue: }
13. Bd2 Qc7 14. Qe2 Nf6 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Rxh5 Rxh5 17. Qxh5 e4
{ This position is equal and both sides have chances.   This sacrifice allows us to attack the b2-pawn and to play along the h8-a1 diagonal. Our next moves are ...Bxb2 @@StartBracket@@if allowed@@EndBracket@@ followed by ...Bf6 back or ...Bd4, ...O-O-O and ...Nbd7.   White's light-squared bishop is not so happy and we can dream about a good knight vs. bad bishop scenario in the future. }
