1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3
{ White keeps the possibility to play 7.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@this transposes to our Nf3 + Bd3 lines@@EndBracket@@  or Nge2  @@StartBracket@@what we are going to study here@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nbd7
{ This is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in the Modern setup where White plays Nf3 + Bd3.   6...O-O  would invite White to play h3-g4 ideas. We want to see where White decides to put his g1-knight before we decide to castle or not. }
7. Nge2 h5
{ We push Harry! Our idea is to take space on the kingside with ...h5-h4 and to dissuade White to play Ng3.  Our typical ideas:   We can play ...Nf8-g6: if we succeed to play ...h4, we have the ...Nh5-f4 idea.  We can play for the ...b5 break with ...a6/...Bd7/...Rb8/...Qa5.  We can play ...Kf8-g8. Then, our king will be in safety. Next, we can build an attack on White's king if he decides to castle. }
8. h3
{ This is too slow and was played in the game Mamedyarov, S. - Finegold, B., 0-1, 2017 we saw in the inspirational games. }
8... h4 9. Be3 Nf8
{ Our knight comes on g6, and our king will be safe on f8 or g8. We don't want to castle kingside because our rook is already active on h8. We could have ideas like ...Rh6-g6 in the future. Next, we want to play with our typical ideas.  Model game: Mamedyarov, S. - Finegold, B., 0-1, 2017.  The important thing here is not to know all the theory by rote but to have all those ideas in your arsenal because they will help you to find the good moves over the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 2: Model Games "]
[Black "Introduction and What we want to avoid"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7
{ In this chapter, we will discuss how to play with Black when White decides to put his light-squared bishop on d3. }
6. Bd3
{ The modern setup − Bd3.  White keeps the choice to develop his knight on f3 or e2. We will have different ideas according to where the knight is going.  Here, it is important to remember that we must play ...Nbd7 first. We are waiting for White to show his cards @@StartBracket@@where he wants to put his knight@@EndBracket@@. We don't play ...O-O yet because White has ideas like h3 followed by g4 to squeeze us. That is what we want to avoid.  Next, we will see three games where strong grandmasters got squeezed by this h3 + g4 plan. I hope three games will be enough to convince you to always play ...Nbd7 first before ...O-O. }
6... Nbd7
{ We will adapt our plan according to whether the knight comes in f3 or e2. }
7. Nf3
{ Now that the knight is on f3, we can castle and there is nothing to worry about.   A@@EndBracket@@  7.Nge2  ,  when the knight comes to e2, we want to take some space on the kingside with a good friend.  7...h5  is our move. I will explain why in the theory section.   B@@EndBracket@@  7.h3  White waits before developing his knight and would like to see us castling. But we don't want to help White, and again, we must use Harry to take some space.  7...h5  is our move. We will see why in the theory section. }
7... O-O { This is our move. I will explain why in the theory section. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 2: Model Games "]
[Black "Garry Kasparov vs. Anthony Miles"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3 O-O
{ That is premature. Now, White can play h3 followed by g4 to squeeze Black.  6...Nbd7  is my recommendation in the theory section. }
7. h3
{ Here, we would like to play ...Nh5 because g4 could be met with ...Nf4. However, it doesn't work here for tactical reasons. }
7... Nbd7
{ 7...Nh5  8.Nxe5  8...dxe5  9.Qxh5  White is winning. Keep this theme in your mind because we will see it again in the theory section. }
8. g4 { This plan is strong, and Black has nothing to do but being cramped. }
8... Ne8 9. Bd3 { Only now the bishop is developed on d3. } 9... a6
{ Trying to find some counterplay on the queenside. } 10. a4
{ No counterplay allowed. The center is closed so we have to play on the flanks. But White squeezed Black on both sides of the board. That is what we want to avoid. }
10... Rb8 11. Rg1 Nc7 12. b3 Re8 13. h4
{ White's king is safe in the center because the position is closed. Black's position is cramped. }
13... b5 { Trying to fight for counterplay, but it's too late. } 14. g5
{ You know something went wrong when Garry is pushing Garry against you. }
14... Nf8 15. h5 { And now Harry comes. } 15... Bd7 16. Nh2 bxc4 17. Bxc4 f5
{ The last bullet. } 18. exf5 Bxf5 19. Nf1 { The knigt comes to e3. } 19... Qd7
20. Ne3 e4 21. Bb2 Bd8 22. Ne2 Qf7 23. Nf4 Bc8 24. Rg4 Qe7 25. Rg3 Qf7 26. Nfg2
{ White reorganizes his pieces while Black is waiting for White to reorganize his pieces. }
26... Na8 27. a5 Nc7 28. Nh4 Nb5 29. g6 hxg6 30. Nxg6 Bf6 31. Bxb5 Rxb5 32. Qc2
Bxb2 33. Qxb2 Nxg6 34. Rxg6 Re5 35. O-O-O Rxh5 36. Rdg1
{ There is nothing to do. } 36... Rh7 37. Nc4 Qf4+ 38. Kb1 Rb7 39. Nxd6 Bf5 40.
Rf6 Qh2 41. Rg3 Qh1+ 42. Ka2
{ Black resigns. White's play was not perfect. But Black was squeezed for so long that it was difficult to find when it was possible to breathe just a little. }
