1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Nbd7 6. Bd3 Be7 7. h3 O-O
{ That is premature. Now, White has time to play g4.  7...h5  is my recommendation in the theory section. }
8. g4 Ne8 9. Nf3 g6
{ Black is trying to use our typical plan. But the ...f5 break is already very difficult to achieve. And White can prevent the ...b5 break with a4. }
10. a3 Ng7 11. Bh6 Kh8 12. Qd2 Nf6 13. O-O-O Ng8 14. Kb1 Nxh6 15. Qxh6 Rg8 16.
Rdg1 Ne8 17. Qe3 Nf6 18. Nd2 Rg7 19. f3 h5
{ Trying to clarify things on the kingside. ...Rb8 + ...a6 + ...Bd7, trying to find counterplay on the queenside with ...b5 was best. }
20. f4 exf4 21. Qxf4 h4 22. Nf3 Nh7 23. g5 a6 { That's too late. } 24. e5 dxe5
25. Nxe5 Kg8 26. Nf3 b5 27. cxb5 c4 28. Bxc4 Bf5+
{ Black tried his best to swindle the game. } 29. Ka2 axb5 30. Nxb5 Bc5 31. Re1
Bf2 32. Re2 Bg3 33. Qd4 Nxg5 34. Nxg5 Qxg5 35. d6 Be6 36. Bxe6 Qxb5 37. Bc4 Qd7
{ But there was nothing to do. } 38. Rd1 Rd8 39. Qf6 Rc8 40. Bb3 Rf8 41. Re7
Qxh3 42. d7 Bc7 43. Re8
{ White wins. I hope those games convinced you that we want to avoid being squeezed by h3 +g4 ideas. }
