[Black "Ashwin, Jayaram (2399) vs. Marin, Mihail (2533)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3 Nbd7 7. Nf3
{ Now we are ready to castle and there is no reason to be afraid of h3 + g4 ideas. }
7... O-O 8. h3 Nh5
{ A good move and my recommendation in the theory section. We are not afraid of g4 because we are ready to jump on the f4-square with the knight. }
9. g4
{ 9.Nxe5  is not possible here because of  9...Nxe5  10.Qxh5  Nxd3+  and White is lost. }
9... Nf4 { This knight is a monster. } 10. Bxf4 exf4
{ Now we want to take control over the dark squares. } 11. Qd2 Ne5
{ 11...Bf6  followed by ...Ne5 is an alternative. } 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Bc2 a6
{ Black wants to put his bishop on d6 and break through with ...b5. } 14. Ba4
Bd6 15. a3 Rb8 { ...b5 is coming. } 16. Ke2
{ The position is closed. White thought his king would be fine in the center. }
16... g6 17. f3 b5 { The breakthrough is very effective here. } 18. cxb5 Qa5
19. b6 c4 { A strong move. Black wants to seize the a7-g1 diagonal. } 20. Bc6
Qxb6 21. Na4 Qa7 22. Rac1 a5 23. Kf1
{ White understands his king is in trouble and flees on g2. } 23... Ba6
{ ...c3+ is on the cards. } 24. Kg2 Rb3 { The rooks join the party. } 25. Rc3
Rfb8 26. Rhc1 Qd4
{ Black has the bishop pair and there are weaknesses in White's camp. White cannot trade the queens because the pawns would be too strong. }
27. Qe2 { 27.Qxd4  exd4  and the pawns will end the game. } 27... Kg7 28. Rd1
Rxb2
{ White resigns.   This game by Marin is instructive. He started by preventing the h3 + g4 plan. Then, he took control over the dark squares and used the ...b5 break to penetrate White's camp. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 2: Model Games "]
[Black "Agafii, Victor vs. Sanduleac, Vasile"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3 O-O
{ 6...Nbd7  is my recommendation in the theory section. After  6...O-O  , White could have played h3 followed by g4. }
7. Nf3
{ This transposes to our Nf3 + Bd3 lines.  7.h3  followed by g4 is best and what we want to avoid. }
7... Nbd7 8. h3 { White should have played h3 before when it was strong. } 8...
Nh5
{ A good move and my recommendation in the theory section. We are not afraid of g4 because we are ready to jump on the f4-square with the knight. }
9. g4 Nf4 { This knight is a monster. } 10. Bxf4 exf4 11. Ne2
{ We don't care about the f4-pawn. The central dark squares are more important. }
11... Bf6 { The bishop is powerful. } 12. Qd2 Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Nxf4 Qf6
{ Black has total control over the dark squares and the b2-pawn is under attack. }
15. Ne2 Qf3 { 15...Bxb2  was possible  16.Rb1  Qf3  17.Rg1  Bf6  . } 16. O-O-O
Qxf2 17. Rdf1
{ The wrong rook!   17.Rhf1  was best.  Qh4  18.Ng1  Bd7  19.Nf3  Qg3  20.Nxe5  Qxe5  21.Qf4  f6  22.Qxe5  fxe5  23.Kd2  g6  and Black is only slightly better. }
17... Qh4 18. Kc2 Bd7
{ White's king is weak. We are ready to break with ...b5 next. } 19. b3 a6 20.
Nf4 b5 { White has big problems now. } 21. Ng2 Qe7 22. Ne3 g6
{ 22...b4  was best. } 23. h4 b4 { Black wants to break with the a-pawn now! }
24. h5 a5 { ...a4 is coming. } 25. hxg6 fxg6
{ Black takes with the f-pawn. This stops the attack on the kingside by trading one pair of rooks. }
26. Rxf8+ Rxf8 27. Qe1 a4 { Black is ready to open the a-file next. } 28. Rf1
{ White understands he is in trouble and want to trade the rooks. } 28... Ra8
{ Of course, we don't want to trade rooks because we need our rook for the incoming attack against White's king. }
29. Kc1 axb3 30. axb3 Bg7
{ Black wants to put his queen in front of the bishop. } 31. Qg3 Ra1+ 32. Bb1
Qe5
{ This allows White to trade queens and to fight a little more.  32...Qxe4  was best. Now, Black has to show his technique to realize his advantage. }
33. Qxe5 Bxe5
{ Black is much better because of the bishop pair and all the weaknesses in White's camp. But he has to show his technique. }
34. g5 Kg7 35. Nc2 Ra8 36. Kd2 Re8 37. Ne1 Bh3 38. Rg1 Bd4 39. Rg3 Bc3+ 40. Kd1
Bd7 41. Nf3 Rf8 42. Ke2 Ra8 43. Bc2 Ra2 44. Kd1 Ra1+ 45. Ke2 Rc1 46. Kd3 Bb2
47. Rg2 Rh1 48. Ke3 Bc1+ 49. Nd2 { The final blunder. } 49... Rh3+
{ The b3-pawn will fall.   49...Bh3  was also strong because after  50.Rf2  Rg1  the g5-pawn is lost. }
50. Kf4 Rc3
{ The bishop has to move from the protection of the b3-pawn, and the knight is pinned. }
51. Bb1 Rxb3 { White resigns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 2: Model Games "]
[Black "Akhmadeev, Vadim (2439) vs. Khismatullin, Denis (2584)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3 O-O
{ I recommend  6...Nbd7  here because White could have played h3 followed by g4. }
7. Nf3
{ This transposes to our Nf3 + Bd3 lines.  7.h3  was followed by g4 best and what we want to avoid. }
7... Nbd7 8. O-O Nh5
{ A good move and my recommendation in the theory section. We will follow our typical plan with a strong attack against White's king. }
9. Re1
{ Here,  9.g3  to control the important f4-square was mandatory. Now, Black is going for the ...f5 breakthrough, and he will be able to push ...f5-f4 in the future. This would allow Black to use our typical plan from the King's Indian Defense. }
9... g6 { Going for our typical plan. } 10. a3 Ng7 11. Bh6 f5 12. Rb1 Kh8
{ ...f4 with our typical plan from the King's Indian Defense was preferable. }
13. Qc2 f4
{ Black wants to harass the bishop on h6 and to launch an attack against White's king. }
14. h3 Rg8 15. Bxg7+ { This just helps Black. } 15... Rxg7
{ The plan is simple: We push Harry and Garry. } 16. Be2 h5 17. Nh2 Nf6 18. Qd1
Bd7 19. b4 cxb4 20. Rxb4 b6
{ Black doesn't want to allow any counterplay on the queenside. } 21. Qd3 Qc8
{ Black wanted to have good control over the g4 square before breaking through with g4.   Best was  21...g5  22.g4  fxg3  23.fxg3  Bxh3  . }
22. Bd1 g5 { Garry is coming. } 23. Ba4 g4 { White's king is in trouble. } 24.
Bxd7 Qxd7 25. Kh1 Rag8 { Everyone joins the party. } 26. Rb2 Bd8
{ This bishop was not doing anything on d8. Black wants to make his bad bishop a useful one by playing ...b5 followed by ...Bb6. }
27. Ne2 b5 { ...Bb6 is coming. } 28. cxb5 Bb6 29. Rf1 gxh3
{ Only the queen has to be mobilized now. } 30. gxh3 Qe8 31. Qf3 Qg6
{ All the pieces are playing together. The king and the e4-pawn are targets. }
32. Rb4 { Trying to defend the e4-pawn but now comes: } 32... Bd4
{ And the e4-pawn will fall. } 33. Rbb1
{ 33.Nxd4  is not possible because of mate in two.  33...Qg1+  34.Rxg1  Rxg1  . }
33... Qxe4 { 33...Nxe4  was best, to continue the attack with all the pieces. }
34. Qxe4 Nxe4 35. Nxd4
{ The game was already lost but this is the final mistake. } 35... Rg1+
{ There is nothing to do against ...Nxf2#. White resigns. } *

