[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 2: Model Games "]
[Black "Pacher, Milan vs. Martinovic, Sasa"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3 Nbd7
{ This is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in the Modern setup where White plays Nf3 + Bd3.   6...O-O  would invite White to play h3-g4 ideas. We want to see where White decides to put his g1-knight before we decide to castle or not. }
7. Nge2 h5
{ We push Harry! Our idea is to take space on the kingside with ...h5-h4 and to dissuade White to play Ng3.  Our typical ideas:   We can play ...Nf8-g6: if we succeed to play ...h4, we have the ...Nh5-f4 idea.  We can play for the ...b5 break with ...a6/...Bd7/...Rb8/...Qa5.  We can play ...Kf8-g8. Then, our king will be in safety. Next, we can build an attack on White's king if he decides to castle. }
8. f3 { This is too slow.  8.h4  is the critical move. } 8... h4 9. Be3 Nf8
{ The knight is going to g6. } 10. Qd2 a6 { This prepares ...b5. } 11. O-O-O
{ This is premature. White's king was fine in the center. Now, Black's plan is simple and straightforward: He wants to break through with ...b5 and attack White's king. }
11... Ng6 { First, Black improves the position of his knight. } 12. Kb1 Bd7
{ Then, he continues with his plan. } 13. g3 Qa5 14. Nc1 b5
{ A strong breakthrough. White has to be careful with his king while Black's king is safe in the center. }
15. N3e2 { Trying to exchange queens. } 15... Qb6
{ Black wants to keep the queens on the board. } 16. Nb3 Rb8 17. Na5 Bd8
{ Attacking the knight but also preparing to activate the bishop later on a5. }
18. Nc6 Bxc6 19. dxc6 Qxc6 20. Nc3
{ A mistake. Now the bishop can come on a5 without any preparation. } 20... Ba5
21. Qc2 Bxc3 { Exchanging the bad bishop against a strong defender. } 22. Qxc3
Nf8 { The knight comes back and wants to relocate on the e6-square. } 23. cxb5
{ This just helps Black. } 23... axb5 24. b4
{ Trying to complicate the position, but that is only complicating White's task. }
24... Ne6 25. bxc5 Nxc5
{ 25...Nd7  to take on c5 with the knight was best to avoid the trade of queens like later in the game. }
26. gxh4 { 26.Bxc5  Qxc5  27.Qxc5  dxc5  and Black is winning. } 26... O-O
{ The king was safe in the center, but Black wants everyone to join the party. Now the f8-rook is coming on c8 with decisive effect. }
27. Bc2 Rfc8 { 27...b4  to break with b3 next was best.  28.Qd2  b3  . } 28.
Bxc5 Qxc5 { This allows White to trade queens. } 29. Qd3
{ White declined the trade of queens. This is in Black's favor. 29.Qxc5 dxc5  was best. Black is slightly better in this endgame but White is not under pressure anymore. }
29... Qb4+ 30. Qb3 Qa5 31. Rd3 Rc5 { Black wants to double on the c-file. } 32.
Qb2 d5 33. Qxe5 { The final mistake.  33.exd5  Nxd5  . } 33... Rbc8 34. Bb3
{ White wants to save his bishop but it's too late.  34.Rc1  dxe4  . } 34...
dxe4 35. Qe7 exd3 36. Qxf7+ Kh8 37. Rg1 Qc7
{ White has no choice but to exchange the queens. White resigns. } *

