[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3 Nbd7
{ This is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in the Modern setup where White plays Nf3 + Bd3.   6...O-O  would invite White to play h3-g4 ideas. We want to see where White decides to put his g1-knight before we decide to castle or not. }
7. Nge2 h5
{ We push Harry! Our idea is to take space on the kingside with ...h5-h4 and to dissuade White to play Ng3.  Our typical ideas:   We can play ...Nf8-g6: if we succeed to play ...h4, we have the ...Nh5-f4 idea.  We can play for the ...b5 break with ...a6/...Bd7/...Rb8/...Qa5.  We can play ...Kf8-g8. Then, our king will be in safety. Next, we can build an attack on White's king if he decides to castle. }
8. h4 Nf8 9. Ng3 g6
{ Black wants to prevent White to reach the f5-square.   9...Ng4  is my recommendation in the theory section.  10.Nf5  Bxf5  11.exf5  Bxh4  12.Ne4  Be7  . }
10. Nge2 Ng4 11. g3 Nh7 12. f3 Ngf6 13. Be3 a6
{ There is nothing to do on the kingside and now Black wants to break through on the queenside. }
14. Qd2 Rb8 15. a4 { Of course, White wants to prevent the ...b5 break. } 15...
Bd7 16. O-O O-O 17. Rab1 a5 18. Nb5 Ne8
{ Black wants to use our typical regrouping plan. } 19. Bh6 Ng7 20. f4 exf4 21.
Qxf4 { The d6-pawn is under attack. } 21... Bxb5 22. axb5 Bf6
{ The bishop is activated on a strong diagonal. } 23. Qf3 Be5 24. Nf4 b6
{ Black closes the position and will play on the rest of the board. } 25. Bc2
Qe8
{ Black wants to play ...Nf6 without allowing the knight to be pinned to the queen on d8. }
26. b3 Nf6 27. Bxg7
{ A mistake. White should have kept this important bishop. } 27... Kxg7 28.
Rbe1 Qe7 29. Kg2 Rbe8 30. Nd3 Ng4 31. Nf2
{ 31.Nxe5  Qxe5  with a good knight vs. bad bishop scenario. } 31... Nf6 32.
Nd3 Nd7 33. Nf4 Bd4 { The knight is ready to jump on e5. } 34. Re2
{ A blunder. } 34... Ne5 { The queen has no square. } 35. Nxh5+
{ Saving the queen and trying to complicate the position, but the game is over. }
35... gxh5 36. Qxh5 Rh8 37. Qf5 Rh6
{ Black wants to trade as many pieces as possible. } 38. Ree1 Reh8 39. Bd1 Rf6
40. Qg5+ Ng6 41. Rf5 Rxf5 42. Qxf5 Rxh4 { The rook cannot be taken. } 43. Bh5
Rf4 { Black uses the same tactical motif. } 44. Qh3 Rxe4 { White resigns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 2: Model Games "]
[Black "Gozzoli, Y. (2583) vs. Finegold, B. (2483)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3 Nbd7
{ This is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in the Modern setup where White plays Nf3 + Bd3.   6...O-O  would invite White to play h3-g4 ideas. We want to see where White decides to put his g1-knight before we decide to castle or not. }
7. Nge2 h5
{ We push Harry! Our idea is to take space on the kingside with ...h5-h4 and to dissuade White to play Ng3.  Our typical ideas:   We can play ...Nf8-g6: if we succeed to play ...h4, we have the ...Nh5-f4 idea.  We can play for the ...b5 break with ...a6/...Bd7/...Rb8/...Qa5.  We can play ...Kf8-g8. Then, our king will be in safety. Next, we can build an attack on White's king if he decides to castle. }
8. h4 { The critical move. } 8... Nf8 { This is my recommendation too. } 9. f3
Ng6 10. g3
{ This is the critical position. White took control over the g4 and the f4-squares. Black must find counterplay on the queenside with our typical ideas. }
10... Bd7 11. a3 Kf8
{ A typical theme. The king will be safe on g8. And the rook is active on h8. }
12. Be3 Kg8 13. b4 b6 14. bxc5 dxc5
{ Black's idea is to play ...Ne8-d6 but  14...bxc5  was best and typical. } 15.
Kd2 Ne8 { The knight is coming on d6. } 16. a4 Nd6
{ This knight is a strong blockader. } 17. Nb5
{ White immediately wants to get rid of the strong blockader on d6. } 17... a6
18. Nxd6 Bxd6
{ The bishop replaces, temporarily, the knight as a blockader. However, bishops are not good blockaders. Black would like his g6-knight to come on d6. Here we can already think about the plan ...Nh8-f7-d6. }
19. Qb3 { The b6-pawn is a target. } 19... Rb8 20. Nc3 Kh7
{ The rook frees the h8-square and comes on f8, where it has more prospects. }
21. Qd1 Rf8 22. Qe2 Kg8 { The king is safe now. } 23. Rhb1 Nh8
{ Only now, Black is ready to relocate his knight. As we said, the bishop is not good as a blockader, and Black would like his knight on d6. }
24. Rb2 f6 { This frees the f7-square for the knight. } 25. Rab1 Qc7 26. Rg1
Nf7 27. g4 hxg4 28. fxg4 b5
{ Black finally finds his counterplay with our typical break on the queenside. }
29. axb5 axb5 30. cxb5 c4 31. Bc2
{ 31.Bxc4  is not possible due to  31...Rfc8  and White is in trouble on the c-file. }
31... Bc5
{ Black wants to trade his bad bishop. This also frees the d6-square. } 32.
Bxc5 Qxc5 33. Qe3 Qd4+ 34. Qxd4 exd4 { The pawns will decide the game. } 35.
Ne2 c3+ 36. Nxc3 dxc3+ 37. Kxc3 { The rest is a matter of technique. } 37...
Rfc8+ { First, Black activates his rook. } 38. Kd2 Ne5
{ Then, the knight jump on the strong e5-square. } 39. Rb3 Nc4+ 40. Kc1 Rxb5
41. Rxb5 Bxb5 42. Rg3 Kf7 43. g5 Nd6 44. Kd2 Rh8 { The h4-pawn is lost. } 45.
Rf3 Rxh4 46. gxf6 gxf6 47. Ke3 Ke7 48. Rg3 Rh2 49. Bd1 Nc4+ 50. Kd4 Rd2+
{ Black trades one piece and wants to put pressure on the weak pawns next. }
51. Kc5 Rxd1 52. Kxb5 Nd6+ { The e4-pawn will fall. } 53. Kc6 Rc1+
{ This important check keeps the White's king cut off. } 54. Kb6 Nxe4 55. Rg4
f5 56. Rg6 Nf6 57. d6+ Ke6
{ The d6-pawn will fall next and the f-pawn will decide the game. White resigns. This game shows how difficult to handle the Czech Benoni can be with White in practical play. }
*

