[White "Theory 2: Model Games "]
[Black "Sande, Oystein (2300) vs. Andersen, Dan (2278)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3 Nbd7
{ This is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in the Modern setup where White plays Nf3 + Bd3.   6...O-O  would invite White to play h3-g4 ideas. We want to see where White decides to put his g1-knight before we decide to castle or not. }
7. Nge2 h5
{ We push Harry! Our idea is to take space on the kingside with ...h5-h4 and to dissuade White to play Ng3.  Our typical ideas:   We can play ...Nf8-g6: if we succeed to play ...h4, we have the ...Nh5-f4 idea.  We can play for the ...b5 break with ...a6/...Bd7/...Rb8/...Qa5.  We can play ...Kf8-g8. Then, our king will be in safety. Next, we can build an attack on White's king if he decides to castle. }
8. O-O { That is a dangerous decision. } 8... h4 9. f4 { Premature. } 9... exf4
{ This gives Black the e5-square. } 10. Bxf4 Ng4
{ A typical maneuver in the Benoni. } 11. Nb5 Nge5 12. h3 a6 13. Na3 Bf6
{ 13...g5  was very strong.  14.Bh2  g4  . } 14. Rb1 O-O
{ Playing for a direct attack against White's king was best. Instead, Black decided to play for the control over the central dark squares, which is also fine.   14...g5  again was very strong. }
15. Nc2 Qe7 { Black gives more control to the e5-square. } 16. Nc3 Nxd3
{ Black wants to control the e5-square and break through with ...b5 next. } 17.
Qxd3 Ne5 18. Qe2 Bd7 { Preparing to break with ...b5. } 19. a3 Rac8
{ A weird move.  19...b5  was best. } 20. Ne3 g6 21. Bh6 Bg7 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23.
Rf4 { A blunder. } 23... Qg5 { The rook and the h3-pawn are under attack. } 24.
Rbf1 Bxh3 25. Ncd1 Rcd8 26. b4 b6 27. Nb2 Bd7
{ Everything is under control now. } 28. Nd3 f6 29. Nxe5 fxe5 30. Rxf8 Rxf8 31.
Rxf8 Kxf8 32. Qf3+ Qf4 { Black would be happy to trade queens. } 33. Kf2 g5 34.
Ke2 g4 35. Qf1
{ 35.Qxf4+  exf4  .  Harry, Garry and Freddy would be too powerful. } 35... Ke7
36. Qe1 g3 37. bxc5 bxc5 38. Kd3 h3 { There is nothing to do against that. }
39. gxh3 Bxh3 40. Qb1 g2 41. Qb7+ Kf6 42. Nxg2 Bxg2 43. Qh7 Bxe4+
{ The simplest. Black is happy to transpose into a winning endgame. } 44. Qxe4
Qxe4+ 45. Kxe4 Kg5 46. Kf3 Kf5 47. Ke3 e4
{ And Black's king is ready to penetrate. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
