[White "Theory 2: Model Games "]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Bd3
{ 6.h3  White waits before developing his pieces. Of course, we don't want to castle because of the g4-idea.  6...Nbd7  Simple. We want White to develop his pieces before we castle or not.  7.g4  We are not afraid by g4 here. This move weakens the f4-square. We can start with ...h6 to prevent g5 and continue with our typical ...Nf8, ...Ng6, ...Nf4.   7.Bd3  Again, we don't want to castle too soon here.  7...h5  ,  we grab space on the kingside by preventing the g4-idea. Our ideas are the same as in our lines where White plays @@StartBracket@@Bd3 + Nge2@@EndBracket@@:  We want to push ...h5-h4. We want to maneuver our knight with ...Nf8-g6-f4. We would like to break with ...b5. Our king is safe on f8 or g8. }
6... Nbd7 7. h3
{ White tries to trick us by playing  7.h3  instead of  7.Nf3  or  7.Nge2  .   There is no need to panic. We need to understand White would like to play g4 and prevent his threat. What is the best way to do that? }
7... h5
{ We push Harry of course! Our ideas are always the same and mentioned in the annotations to 6.Bd3.   Notes:  8.Nge2  transposes toMamedyarov, S. - Finegold, B., 0-1, 2017. }
