[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 2: Model Games "]
[Black "Guramishvili, Sopiko (2281) vs. Ovod, Evgenija (2430)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. h3
{ White waits before developing his pieces. Of course, Black doesn't want to castle because of the g4-idea. }
6... Nbd7
{ This is a good waiting move. Black develops a piece and waits to see where the bishop is going. }
7. Bd3 h5
{ Black grabs space on the kingside by preventing the g4-idea. Our ideas are the same as in the lines where White plays @@StartBracket@@Bd3 + Nge2@@EndBracket@@:  We want to push ...h5-h4. We want to maneuver our knight with ...Nf8-g6-f4. We would like to break with ...b5. Our king is safe on f8 or g8. }
8. Nf3 { This move does nothing to prevent ...h4. } 8... h4
{ Black is ready to take control over the f4-square. } 9. Be3 Nh5 10. Qd2 Nf8
{ The knight is ready to come on g6. } 11. Ne2 Bd7
{ Black doesn't forget the ...b5 rupture. } 12. b4 b6
{ Black is ready to answer bxc5 with ...bxc5. } 13. a4 a5
{ A good move! Black wants to determine the queenside structure. White has to take on c5 or close the position with b5. }
14. b5
{ The position is closed. For this reason, Black changes his plan. He is not in a hurry to play ...Ng6-f4. Instead, he wants to break with ...f5. }
14... g6 15. O-O-O f5 16. Qc2
{ 16.exf5  is bad for White.  16...gxf5  17.Bc2  e4  18.Ng5  Rg8  19.Ne6  Nxe6  20.dxe6  Bxe6  and Black is much better. }
16... Ng7
{ There was nothing wrong with  16...f4  .  Next, Black can play ...Qc7, ...O-O-O and prepare the ...g4 break. }
17. g3 Bf6
{ Black slowly improves the position of his pieces. Black would like to open the h8-a1 diagonal for his bishop. }
18. Rdg1 hxg3 19. fxg3 Qe7 { Black's king will be safe on the queenside. } 20.
h4 O-O-O
{ The position is locked on the queenside so the king will be safe. Next, Black can start to play on the kingside. }
21. Rf1 Kc7 22. Bd2 Re8 23. Ne1 fxe4
{ This helps Black to put his pieces on good squares. } 24. Bxe4 Bg4 25. Nf3
Nf5 26. Rhg1 Qg7 { Black wants to control the f-file. } 27. Qd3 Re7 28. Nh2
Bxe2 { Black removes the defender of the d4-square. } 29. Qxe2 Nd4
{ The knight is strong on d4. } 30. Qd3 Rf7
{ Black wants to fight for the control of the f-file. } 31. Ng4 Be7
{ Black wants to keep his bishop and is ready to trade a pair of rooks. } 32.
Kb2 Kd8 33. Rxf7 Qxf7 34. Rf1 Qg7 35. Rf2 g5
{ A good move. Black undermines the h4-pawn and wants to open the h-file. } 36.
hxg5 Bxg5 { Black wants to trade his bad bishop. } 37. Ne3 Nd7
{ This knight was dead on f8 for a long time! It was not so important because of the closed character of the position. But now, Black decides to improve his position. And let me say: Black won the game because he activated this knight! }
38. Bc3 Bxe3 39. Qxe3 Rh3 { The g3-pawn is under attack. } 40. Rg2 Nf6
{ Now the knight is ready to join the action. } 41. Bd3 Nh5
{ A new piece attacks the g3-pawn. } 42. Be1 { 42.Qe1  was best. } 42... Nf4
{ The knight was doing nothing on f8 a few moves ago. Now, this is a killer on f4. This shows how the activation of one's pieces can change everything. }
43. Rg1 Nxd3+ 44. Qxd3
{ What now?   White's king is weak. The knight is a monster. The rook is ready to join the attack with ...Rh2+. Only the queen needs to be activated now. }
44... e4 { The queen joins the attack. } 45. Qc3 Rh2+ 46. Kb1 Qg4
{ The queen will reach the 2nd rank next with decisive effect. } 47. Bd2 Qe2
48. Bg5+ Ke8 49. Kc1 Qf2
{ All the black pieces work together against White's king while White's pieces are not coordinated. White resigns. }
