[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. h3
{ White waits before developing his pieces. Of course, Black doesn't want to castle because of the g4-idea. }
6... Nbd7
{ This is a good waiting move. Black develops a piece and waits to see where the bishop is going. }
7. Be3 { White waits before developing his light-squared bishop. } 7... h5
{ Black grabs space on the kingside by preventing the g4-idea. Our ideas are the same as in the lines where White plays @@StartBracket@@Bd3 + Nge2@@EndBracket@@:  We want to push ...h5-h4. We want to maneuver our knight with ...Nf8-g6-f4. We would like to break with ...b5. Our king is safe on f8 or g8. }
8. Bd3
{ The bishop is developed on d3 now. However, this does nothing to prevent ...h4. }
8... h4 9. Nf3 { Black is ready to take control over the f4-square. } 9... Nh5
10. Ne2 Nf8 11. Qd2 a6
{ This move asks White if he is sure he wants to castle queenside. } 12. O-O-O
{ The computer says this position is equal. However, I believe Black is already slightly better.   Black is ready to take control over the f4-square after ...Ng6. Black's king is safe in the center.  ...b5 is coming with an attack against White's king. Black has more experience than White with all our ideas in this position. }
12... Nf6 13. Kb1 Ng6 14. Nh2 Rb8 { ...b5 is coming. } 15. f4
{ White understands ...b5 will be strong and that he needs to do something. However, f4 is premature and only gives Black the e5-square. }
15... exf4 16. Bxf4 b5 { Black is coming for White's king. } 17. cxb5 axb5 18.
Nf3 Nd7
{ The knight is rerouted to the e5-square. The bishop can come on f6 next to put pressure on the h8-a1 diagonal. }
19. Bh2 Nde5 20. Nf4 Nxf4 21. Bxf4 Nxd3 22. Qxd3 O-O 23. e5 Ra8 24. exd6 Bf6
{ This bishop is a sniper and White needs to do something about it. } 25. Be5
g6 { ...Bf5 is the threat. } 26. Ka1 { The king feels exposed on a1. } 26...
Bf5 27. Qc3 Bxe5 28. Nxe5 Qxd6 { The game is over. } 29. Nc6 Rxa2+ 30. Kxa2
Ra8+ 31. Na5 b4 32. Qc1 b3+
{ White resigns. This game is an instructive one. Nisipeanu used all of our typical ideas in this game. The natural O-O-O was the mistake of the game because it allowed Black to take the initiative until the end of the game. }
33. Kxb3 Qb6+ 34. Ka2 Rxa5# *

