[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 3: 6.Nge2!?"]
[Black "Mastrovasilis, Athanasios (2518) vs. Fakhiridou, Ekaterini (2274)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nge2
{ This is a tricky move you should be aware of. White doesn't plan to castle but to play Ng3 followed by h4. That is why Black should not castle too soon and prevent White's plan instead. }
6... O-O
{ That was premature. White is now ready to execute his plan and launch an attack against Black's king.   6...h5  is my recommendation for the course. }
7. Ng3 Ne8
{ Black wants to use our standard regrouping plan. The problem is that this only helps White. }
8. h4 { Black's king feels insecure. } 8... g6
{ This only gives White a hook. } 9. h5
{ The position is already very difficult for Black. } 9... Bg5
{ Logical. Black wants to trade his bad bishop. } 10. Bd2 Qf6
{ 10...Bxd2+  However, Black should wait for White to exchange on g5. This only helps White to develop his queen and be ready for queenside castling.  11.Qxd2  . }
11. Qc1 { White wants Black to trade on d2. } 11... Bf4 12. Nge2 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2
{ White is clearly better. } 13... a6
{ Black wants to find counterplay on the queenside. } 14. g3
{ 14.a4  was best. } 14... Nc7 15. a4 { This prevents ...b5. } 15... Bg4 16.
Ng1
{ A good move. White wants to keep pieces for the attack and particularly the good ones. }
16... Re8
{ 16...Bxh5  just helps Black to open the h-file.  17.Qh6  Qg7  18.Qxg7+  Kxg7  19.f3  f5  20.exf5  Rxf5  21.g4  . }
17. a5 { The queenside is locked for the time being. } 17... Bf3 18. Rh4 Nd7
19. Qe3 Bxh5 20. f3 { 20.Qh6  was also fine. } 20... Qe7 21. O-O-O
{ White's attack is faster. This move helps to bring the d-rook in the attack if necessary. }
21... Reb8 22. Rh1
{ g4 is coming but  22.Rh2  was more precise.  The h1-square should have been reserved for the d1-rook. }
22... Nf6 23. Be2 b6 { The position is already lost for Black. } 24. g4 bxa5
25. Nh3 Nce8 26. Rdg1 a4 27. gxh5 a3 28. bxa3 Qb7
{ White is winning. Black has some counterplay on the queenside, so White must stay focus until the end of the game. }
29. Kc2 Qb2+ 30. Kd3 { The king will be safe on d3. } 30... Rb3 31. Qd2
{ The trade of queens only favors White. } 31... Qxa3 32. hxg6 fxg6 33. Ra1 Qb4
34. Rhb1
{ Logical. White has a material advantage and wants to trade all the pieces. }
34... Ng7 35. Rxb3 Qxb3 36. Rb1 Qa3 37. Qb2 Qxb2 38. Rxb2
{ 'And the rest is a matter of technique.' } 38... Ra7 39. Rb6
{ White doesn't waste time and activates his pieces. The d6-pawn is under attack. }
39... Nge8
{ The knight is now compelled to defend the d6-pawn. What is your worst piece? How can you activate it? }
40. Bd1
{ The d1-bishop is bad and was useless on e2. This move allows White to relocate the bishop on a4, where it puts pressure on the e8-knight. }
40... h6 41. Ba4 Kf7 42. Ne2 { White now wants to break through with f4. }
42... Ke7 43. f4 exf4 44. Nhxf4 g5 45. e5 gxf4 46. exf6+ Nxf6 47. Nxf4 Ra8 48.
Rb7+ Kf8 49. Ng6+
{ From move 38, White didn't give any time to Black to find counterplay. Only one piece needs to be activated now. }
49... Kg8 50. Ke3 { The king also wants to improve his position. } 50... h5 51.
Kf4 Ng4 52. Kg5 Ne3 53. Kxh5
{ Black resigns. This game is instructive to show how dangerous the Nge2 + h4 plan can be. White obtains a risk-free game where only Black is under pressure. }
