[Black "6.Nge2!? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nge2
{ This is a tricky move you should be aware of. White doesn't plan to castle but to play Ng3 followed by h4. That is why Black should not castle too soon and prevent White's plan instead. }
6... h5
{ We must prevent White's idea with Harry! This is quite similar to our lines against the Modern @@StartBracket@@Bd3 + Nge2@@EndBracket@@. However, White's bishop is still on f1, and I believe this is in Black's favor.  We always have the same typical ideas:  - We can play ...Nf8-g6: if we succeed to play ...h4, we have the ...Nh5-f4 idea.  - We can play for the ...b5 break with ...a6/...Bd7/...Rb8/...Qa5.  - We can play ...Kf8-g8. Then, our king will be in safety. Next, we can build an attack on White's king if he decides to castle. }
7. h4
{ White stops ...h4.   - The knight on e2 is misplaced.   - Ng3 is always meet with ...g6.   In general, the best for White is to admit his mistake by Ng1 back to develop his kingside properly. }
7... Na6 { Next, we want to play ...Nc7 and prepare the ...b5 rupture. } *

