1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nge2
{ This is a tricky move you should be aware of. White doesn't plan to castle but to play Ng3 followed by h4. That is why Black should not castle too soon and prevent White's plan instead. }
6... h5
{ We must prevent White's idea with Harry! This is quite similar to our lines against the Modern @@StartBracket@@Bd3 + Nge2@@EndBracket@@. However, White's bishop is still on f1, and I believe this is in Black's favor.  We always have the same typical ideas:  - We can play ...Nf8-g6: if we succeed to play ...h4, we have the ...Nh5-f4 idea.  - We can play for the ...b5 break with ...a6/...Bd7/...Rb8/...Qa5.  - We can play ...Kf8-g8. Then, our king will be in safety. Next, we can build an attack on White's king if he decides to castle. }
7. h4 g6 { 7...Na6  is my recommendation. } 8. g3 Na6
{ Black wants to play ...Nc7, ...Bd7, ...Rb8 and prepare the ...b5 rupture. }
9. a3 Bd7 10. f3 { White controls the g4 and the f4-squares. } 10... Nh7 11. f4
{ This gives Black control over the e5-square. } 11... Bf6
{ Black wants to use the h8-a1 diagonal for his bishop. } 12. Bg2 exf4 13. Bxf4
Qe7 { This defends the d6-pawn and controls the e5-square. } 14. Qb3 Bg4
{ There was nothing wrong with ...Rb8. } 15. Nc1 g5
{ This is premature.  15...O-O-O  16.Nb5  Kb8  and everything is defended. }
16. hxg5 Nxg5 17. Nb5 { The d6-pawn is under attack. } 17... Rd8 18. O-O
{ This allows Black to seize the initiative.   18.Qe3  and White is fine.  18...Bxb2  is met with  19.Bxg5  f6  20.Rb1  Bxc1  21.Qxc1  fxg5  22.O-O  and White is better. }
18... Nh3+ { 18...h4  was good. } 19. Kh2
{ A blunder.   A@@EndBracket@@  19.Bxh3  was necessary.  19...Bxh3  20.Re1  Be5  .  The position is equal. However, White's king feels more insecure than Black's one.   B@@EndBracket@@  19.Kh1  h4  And White's king has problems. }
19... h4 { Black is ready to open up the h-file. } 20. Nd3 hxg3+ 21. Kxg3 Bd4
{ But now, the queen is coming to h4 with decisive effect. White resigns. } *

