[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 3: Model Games "]
[Black "De Souza, Mauro Guimaraes (2405) vs. Rocha, Wellington Carlos (2325)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nge2
{ This is a tricky move you should be aware of. White doesn't plan to castle but to play Ng3 followed by h4. That is why Black should not castle too soon and prevent White's plan instead. }
6... h5
{ We must prevent White's idea with Harry! This is quite similar to our lines against the Modern @@StartBracket@@Bd3 + Nge2@@EndBracket@@. However, White's bishop is still on f1, and I believe this is in Black's favor.  We always have the same typical ideas:  - We can play ...Nf8-g6: if we succeed to play ...h4, we have the ...Nh5-f4 idea.  - We can play for the ...b5 break with ...a6/...Bd7/...Rb8/...Qa5.  - We can play ...Kf8-g8. Then, our king will be in safety. Next, we can build an attack on White's king if he decides to castle. }
7. f3 { This move doesn't prevent ...h4. } 7... h4 8. Be3 Nbd7
{ The knight is coming to g6 from f8. } 9. Qd2 Nf8 10. Nc1 Ng6 11. Bd3
{ 11.Nd3  was best. } 11... Nh5 { Black's knights are very well placed. } 12.
N1e2 Nhf4 13. Rg1
{ Defending the g2-pawn.   13.Nxf4  exf4  14.Bxf4   14.Bf2  h3  followed by ...Ne5 and ...Bf6.  14...Nxf4  15.Qxf4  Bg5  and the queen is trapped. }
13... h3 14. g3 Ng2+ 15. Kd1 a6 { Black wants to break with ...b5. } 16. a4
{ White immediately prevents Black's plan. } 16... Nxe3+
{ This was an important bishop. Now, Black wants to active his bad-bishop on g5 at the right moment. }
17. Qxe3 Bd7 { Black slowly prepares the ...b5 break. } 18. Kc2 Bg5
{ Black activates his bad-bishop and wants to provoke f4. } 19. f4 Bf6 20. f5
Nf8 21. g4 Bg5 22. Qf3 Qa5 23. Ra3 Rb8 24. Rg3 Qc7 25. b3 Nh7
{ Black sacrifices the h3-pawn. He claims he will be the one taking advantage of the open h-file. }
26. Rxh3 Ke7 { The rooks are connected. } 27. Rh5 g6 28. Rh3
{ 28.fxg6  fxg6  29.Rh3  Qc8  30.Rg3  Bh4  31.Rg2  Ng5  32.Qe3  Rf8  and Black is much better. }
28... Qa5 { Black is threatening to play ...b5. } 29. Ra2
{ White prevents the ...b5 break with tactics. } 29... Qb4 30. Qf2 Nf6 31. Rf3
{ Black succeeded in controlling the h-file. } 31... gxf5 32. exf5 b5
{ Time to break through! } 33. axb5 axb5 34. cxb5 Qxg4
{ Black's pieces are well coordinated. } 35. Rg3 Qh5 36. Qg2 Bf4 37. Nxf4 exf4
38. Rf3 Ng4 { Black's knight penetrates. } 39. Qe2+ Ne3+
{ 39...Ne5  was best. } 40. Rxe3+ { This is a mistake. } 40... fxe3 41. Qxe3+
Kf8
{ There are too many weaknesses in White's camp while Black's king is safe on f8. }
42. Ra6 Bxf5 { White decided to throw in the towel here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 4A: Fianchetto Variation (Nf3 before g3)"]
[Black "Nf3 before g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. Nf3
{ White plays Nf3 first and doesn't show his cards yet. } 6... Nbd7
{ We play ...Nbd7 first because we want to know if White's bishop is going on e2, Classical setup, or d3, Modern setup.   6...Nbd7  is an important move to remember. We are ready to transpose in our Classical setup if White plays  7.Be2  .   6...O-O  would transpose in 'What we want to avoid' where White squeezes Black with h3 + g4 ideas. }
7. g3
{ The Fianchetto Variation − White wants to put his bishop on g2 and try to break with f4. An alternative is to play Bh3 trying to exchange his bad bishop against Black's good one.   Here, I will recommend you two moves:  7...a6  , trying to go Benko style @@StartBracket@@main recommendation@@EndBracket@@, and  7...O-O  , with our typical regrouping plan on the kingside @@StartBracket@@alternative@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 { We are threatening to play ...b5 if White plays Bg2. } 8. a4
{ This move has to be played. } 8... O-O 9. Bg2
{ The main move for Black here is to play  9...Ne8  and to use our typical regrouping  plan @@StartBracket@@...g6 - ...Ng7 followed by ...f5@@EndBracket@@.   This is the move Andreikin used in our model game: Gajewski, Grzegorz  (2616)  - Andreikin, Dmitry  (2688)  , 0-1, 2012. You can follow this game or try my recommendation. }
9... Nh5
{ Our plan is the same as with ...Ne8. But I think our knight is better placed here because we give White a chance to go wrong:  - g4 is always met with ...Nf4  (our knight is strong)  and after Bxf4 we will have control over the central e5-square @@StartBracket@@...Bf6 - ...Ne5 - ...Qe7@@EndBracket@@.   - if White plays  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Qxh5  Bg4  and the queen is trapped. }
10. O-O g6 11. Bh6 Ng7
{ And now we come back to our typical regrouping plan. We want to break with ...f5. }
*

