1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. g3
{ White is transparent about the fact he wants to play the Fianchetto Variation. }
6... O-O
{ 6...Na6!  is an interestingalternative I will show you later in the chapter. }
7. h4
{ Taking space on the kingside. White wants to play Bh3 to exchange his bad bishop. }
7... Na6 8. Bh3 Bxh3 9. Nxh3 { The knight will be misplaced here. } 9... b5
{ Benko style! We sac this pawn because we want to take control of the b- and a-files. Black will have effective counterplay on the queenside. The knight can't take on b5 because of the e4-pawn. }
10. cxb5 Nc7 { The knight puts pressure on the b5-pawn. } 11. a4 Qd7
{ This move prevents White from castling. Our plan is to play ...Rfb8 followed by ...a6 and we will have good compensation for the pawn. For instance: }
12. Kf1 Rfb8 13. Kg2 a6 14. bxa6 Nxa6 { Black has a good game. } *

