[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 4: Model Games "]
[Black "Gelfand, Boris (2723) vs. Aronian, Levon (2752)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. g3 Nbd7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. Nge2
Ne8 { Aronian goes for our typical regrouping plan. } 9. O-O g6 10. Be3
{ 10.Bh6  was best. } 10... Ng7 11. Kh1 Kh8
{ It was already possible to play ...f5 but Aronian wanted his king to be safe and our plan to be completed. }
12. Qd2 Nf6 { Again, ...f5 was already possible. } 13. f4 exf4 14. gxf4 Re8
{ A good move. } 15. Bg1
{ 15.e5  was strong.  15...Ng4  16.Bg1  Bf8  17.h3  Qh4  18.Nb5  18...Bf5  19.Nc7  dxe5  20.Nxa8  Bd6  .  Black will win the a8-knight and the good placement of his pieces will gives him good compensation for the exchange. }
15... Ngh5 16. e5 dxe5 17. fxe5 Ng4 18. Ne4 Nxe5 19. d6 Bf8
{ The position is complicated for both sides but White stands better because of his strong d-pawn. }
20. Bxc5 Bg7 { The bishop is powerful on g7. } 21. Rac1 b6
{ Black develops his light-squared bishop with tempo. } 22. Bg1 Bb7 23. c5
{ This is a mistake and allows Black to take the initiative. } 23... bxc5 24.
Nxc5 Bxg2+ 25. Kxg2 Qc8
{ White's king is weak and Black must underline this fact; ...Qg4+ is coming. }
26. Nd4 Qg4+ 27. Kh1 Rad8 { Attacking the strong d-pawn. } 28. Nb7
{ This is a mistake.  28.Nb5  was best. The position was complicated for many moves and White was certainly under time pressure. }
28... Rd7 29. Rc7 Qh3
{ 29...Ng3+  is the same.  30.hxg3  Qh3+  31.Qh2  Qxf1  . } 30. Qg2 Ng3+ 31.
Qxg3 Qxf1 32. Qg2 Qa6
{ This allows White to fight a little. Trading the queens was best. However, the position is complicated. It is easy to understand Black's practical choice.   32...Qxg2+  33.Kxg2  Rb8  ,  both the b7-knight and the b2-pawn are threatened.  34.Na5  Rxb2+  35.Kh1  Rb8  36.Nac6  Rxc7  37.dxc7  Rc8  38.Nxa7  Rxc7  39.Nab5  Rc1  40.a4  Bh6  41.Kg2  Ra1  42.Nc3  Bd2  43.Nb3  Rxg1+  44.Kxg1  Bxc3  .  The a-pawn will fall and Black can convert this without problems. }
33. Nc5 { White blunders the d6-pawn immediately. } 33... Qxd6 34. Nb5 Qxc7
{ Not necessary but a good a beautiful move! } 35. Nxc7 Rxc7 36. Qd5 Rcc8 37.
Nb7 Rc1 38. Nd6 Rd8 39. Kg2 Rc2+ 40. Kg3 Kg8 { Black prevents any fork on f7. }
41. Kh3 h5 { The king will be safer on h7. } 42. Bxa7 Rxb2 43. Bc5 Kh7 44. Bd4
Rd2 45. Qa5 { This is met with } 45... Rd3+ 46. Kg2 Rxd6 47. Bxe5 R6d5
{ And the bishop is lost. White resigns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 4: Model Games "]
[Black "Doroshkievich, Vladimir K vs. Arutiunov, Albert"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. g3 O-O 7. Bh3
{ White wants to trade his bad bishop against Black's good one. This strategy is interesting, but the knight on h3 will be misplaced. Next, Black wants to go Benko style. }
7... Bxh3 8. Nxh3 b5 { Benko style! } 9. cxb5 a6 10. bxa6 Qd7
{ The knight is misplaced and needs to move. } 11. Ng5 Nxa6 12. h4 c4
{ A typical move in the Benko/Benoni. Black would like to put a knight on d3. Black is a pawn down but already slightly better. }
13. Kf1 { White wants to castle by hand. } 13... Nc5
{ The knight is ready to jump on the d3-square. } 14. Kg2 Rfb8
{ Black has good counterplay on the queenside. } 15. Qe2 Nd3 16. Rb1
{ 16.b3  trying to undermine the c-pawn was best.  16...Qc8  17.bxc4  is a blunder.  17...Qxc4  18.Bd2  Rb2  And now we understand why we go Benko style. }
16... Bd8
{ The bishop is doing nothing on e7 and Black would like to activate it with ...Ba5. }
17. b3 Ba5 18. Bd2 Bxc3 19. Bxc3 Qg4
{ A strong move! There are many weaknesses to exploit in White's camp, and the trade of queens only helps Black. }
20. Qxg4 Nxg4 21. Nh3 Rxa2 22. bxc4 Rc8
{ Black wants to keep both rooks on the board. } 23. Be1 h5
{ The only Black's problem  (king's safety)  is solved, and this move also supports the strong knight on g4. }
24. Rb3 Nc5 25. Rf3 f6
{ There was nothing wrong with ...Nxe4. But Black wanted to restrict the h3-knight. }
26. Bb4 Nxe4
{ The game is lost for White. There is no chance for counterplay. } 27. Rc1 Rb8
28. Ba3 Ra8 29. Bb4 Rb2 30. Be1 Raa2 31. Kg1 Rc2
{ Trading an active rook for a passive one was not necessary. But Black's idea was to take the c4-pawn next. }
32. Rxc2 Rxc2 33. Ra3 Rxc4 34. Ra1 Nh6 35. Kf1 Rd4 36. Ra5 Nc5
{ The d5-pawn will fall. White resigns.   This game is instructive to see how effective Black's counterplay can be if he is allowed to go Benko-style against Bh3 / h4 - Bh3 ideas. }
*

