[White "Theory 4: Model Games "]
[Black "Ayupov, Damir (2312) vs. Ovetchkin, Roman (2557)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. g3 Na6
{ An interesting alternative. Black delays kingside castling because he has ideas with ...h5-h4. }
7. Bg2 Nc7 8. Nge2
{ The most common move in the position. But now, Black seizes the initiative. }
8... h5
{ A strong move and the reason why we played 6...Na6. Black wants to attack the fianchetto with Harry. Black threatens ...h4. }
9. h3 { This is too slow and does nothing against our threat. } 9... h4 10. g4
Nd7
{ Black wants to trade his bad bishop on g5. The ...f5 break will be difficult to achieve. So, Black wants to play for the ...b5 break and/or the control over the h6-c1 diagonal. }
11. O-O Rb8 12. Be3 Bg5 13. f4
{ Premature. This gives Black control over the e5-square.  13.Bxg5  was best. }
13... exf4 14. Nxf4 Ne5
{ Black won the e5-square. He is now ready to break through with ...b5. } 15.
Qe2 a6 16. Rab1 b5 { Black achieved a lot out of the opening. } 17. cxb5 Nxb5
{ Black would like to jump on d4 with his knight. } 18. Nxb5 Rxb5
{ There was nothing wrong with  18...axb5  . } 19. Rfc1 O-O 20. b3 Bd7 21. Rb2
Rb6
{ Black wants to put his bishop on b5. His threat will be to take the f4-knight and to fork both rooks with ...Nd3. }
22. Bf1
{ White wants to prevent Black's plan. However, it is important to note that the bishop is not defending the e4-pawn anymore. }
22... Bb5 23. Qf2
{ Black accepts to trade his good bishop against White's bad bishop because the e4-pawn is weak. }
23... Bxf1 24. Qxf1 Rb4
{ Black targets the e4-pawn immediately. White's queen is not able to defend the pawn because of the ...Nd3 threat. }
25. Rf2 Rxe4 { This is a big pawn. } 26. Re1 Re8 27. Kg2 Qa8
{ The d5-pawn is under attack. } 28. Rfe2 Bxf4 29. Bxf4 Rxe2+
{ White resigns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 4: Model Games "]
[Black "Pelletier, Yannick (2515) vs. Hickl, Joerg (2555)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2 Na6
{ An interesting alternative. Black delays kingside castling because he has ideas with ...h5-h4. }
8. Nf3 Nc7 9. O-O a6 { Black wants to play for the ...b5 rupture. } 10. a4 b6
{ This prevents a5. Next, Black will continue with his plan @@StartBracket@@...Rb8 and ...b5@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Ne1 Rb8 12. Nd3 b5 { Black achieved the ...b5 break with success. } 13. b3
{ White tries to keep everything under control. } 13... Nd7
{ This move is an important one to remember. The bishop is allowed to reach g5 or f6. And the knight wants to reach b6 to put pressure on White's structure. }
14. Qc2 Bf6
{ 14...bxc4  was best.  15.bxc4  ,  Black's plan could have been to play ...Ne8 followed by ...Bg5 and to continue with ...f5. }
15. Be3 bxc4 16. bxc4 Nb6 { The c4-pawn is under attack. } 17. Nb1 Re8
{ 17...a5  to prevent a5 was best.  18.Bd2  Ra8  .  Next, Black wants to reach the b4-square with his knight. White needs to be careful with his pawn weaknesses. }
18. Nd2 { 18.a5  was strong. } 18... a5
{ Black is ready to play ...Na6-b4. The a5-pawn turned into a weakness, but White had to be prevented from playing a5. }
19. Nb3 { White immediately targets Black's weakness. } 19... Na6 20. Nxa5
{ White is up a pawn for the time being. But Black is ready to get his pawn back. }
20... Nxd5 21. Bd2
{ A mistake.  21.cxd5  was best.  21...Qxa5  22.Rfb1  White is better. Next, he wants to play Nb2-c4 and the game would have been difficult for Black. }
21... Ne7 22. Rfd1 Qc7 23. Rab1 Bg4 24. Rxb8 Nxb8
{ Black wants to install a knight on d4. } 25. f3 Be6
{ Black is slightly better. The c4 and a4-pawns are weak. Black would like to trade the dark-square bishop and to install a knight on d4. }
26. Rb1 Nec6 27. Nxc6 Nxc6
{ Black's knight is ready to jump on d4 at the right moment. } 28. Ne1 Ra8
{ Black activates his rook and targets the weak a4-pawn. } 29. Bf1 h6
{ A strong move. This move gives Black's king a luft and prepares ...Bg5. } 30.
Bc3
{ White understands Black's idea and wants to prevent the trade of the bishops. }
30... Bg5
{ The bishop became useful. Activating the bishop via d8-a5 was also a strong alternative. Only Black's queen needs to find a good square now. }
31. Ng2 Qa7 { The a4-pawn is attacked. } 32. Ra1 Nd4
{ 32...Bd8  was best. The bishop is ready to reach a5 next. } 33. Qd1 h5
{ Black wants to weaken White's kingside structure. } 34. h4 Bh6 35. Bd3 Rb8
36. g4 hxg4 37. fxg4 Bf4 38. Bf1 Qd7 { Black attacks the g4-pawn. } 39. Nxf4
exf4 40. Bxd4 Bxg4 41. Bh3 { The final blunder. } 41... Bxh3 42. Bc3 d5
{ Black frees the way for his rook. } 43. cxd5 Rb6 44. Ra2 Rg6+ 45. Kh1 Rg3
{ With an irresistible attack. White resigns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 4: Model Games "]
[Black "Candela Perez, Jose vs. Teran Alvarez, Ismael"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This game is a short one. But the game is instructive to see how much White needs to be cautious. }
1... Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. g3 Na6
{ An interesting alternative. Black delays kingside castling because he has ideas with ...h5-h4. }
7. Bg2
{ The knight is useful on c7 to help with the ...b5 rupture. It also allows waiting to see where White develops his knight. }
7... Nc7 8. f4
{ Developing a piece was best, but there is nothing wrong with this move. }
8... exf4 9. gxf4 Ng4
{ My recommendation for the course. White has to be careful. } 10. Nf3 Bh4+
{ White has to lose the right to castle. } 11. Kf1
{ 11.Nxh4  is met with  11...Qxh4+  12.Kd2  Qf2+  13.Qe2  Qxf4+  and Black is slightly better. }
11... O-O { Black puts his king in safety and brings a new attacker. } 12. h3
{ A mistake. The h2-pawn was covering the important g3-square. } 12... Nf2 13.
Qe1 { Black can't take on h1. But he can take advantage of the g3-hole. } 13...
Bg3 { Now the h1-rook is under attack. } 14. Rg1
{ White's king feels insecure. } 14... Re8
{ Black wants to open the e-file for his rook but  14...f5  was best. } 15. Ne2
{ A terrible blunder. White was under pressure and gave a pawn for nothing. }
15... Rxe4 16. Qc3 { And now comes: } 16... Rxe2
{ White's king is brought to the center. Black's plan is simple: ...Bf5 + ...Bd3+. }
17. Kxe2 Bf5 18. Ng5 { White frees the f3-square for his king. } 18... Bh4
{ Now, Kf3 doesn't come with tempo. } 19. Be3
{ White wants to block the e-file. } 19... Qe7
{ Black wants to put maximum pressure along the e-file. } 20. Kd2 b5
{ White is under a lot of pressure. } 21. Raf1 Re8
{ All the white pieces are paralyzed. } 22. Bf3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  22.Bxf2  is not possible because of  22...Qe2+  23.Kc1  Bxf2  and White's position collapses.  24.Rxf2  Qxf2   B@@EndBracket@@  22.Rxf2  Bxf2  23.Bxf2  Qe2+  24.Kc1  Qxf2  . }
22... b4 23. Qb3 Nb5
{ That was not necessary.  23...Nxh3  was best.  24.Nxh3  Bxh3  . } 24. Re1
{ Black's idea was to meet  24.cxb5  with  24...c4  and the queen has no square. }
24... Nd3 25. Re2 Qf6 26. cxb5 Nxf4 27. Qc4
{ 27.Bxf4  is not possible because of  27...Qd4+  28.Kc1  Rxe2  29.Bxe2  Qxf4+  30.Kd1  Qd4+  31.Kc1  Qxg1+  32.Kd2  Bxg5+  33.Qe3  Bxe3  A beautiful combination. }
27... Nxe2
{ 27...Qxb2+  was best.  28.Kd1  Nxe2  29.Bxe2  and everything falls. } 28. Rb1
{ White was under pressure all the game and gave a rook for free. } 28... Bxb1
{ White resigns.   White didn't play the best game of his life. However, I'm certain this game is instructive to show how White has to be cautious in the opening. That is the reason why I decided to include it in our model games. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 5: 4.dxe6?!"]
[Black "The position after 4.dxe6? fxe6 - What really matters"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. dxe6
{ This is not a good move but one you will encounter from time to time by people who will be shocked by our 3...e5!?  This capture is a typical mistake at the amateur's level. Black is already slightly better, and White has to be cautious. }
4... fxe6
{ Black is ready to take control over the center with ...d5.   We will see how to play against the most common moves at the club player's level, but also again the most common move at the master level:  5.Nc3  ,  5.Nf3  ,  5.Bg5  ,  5.g3  .  In this chapter, I will show you in great detail how to take advantage when White is playing 5.Nc3, which is the most common move. This should help you to understand the typical ideas in this position and how to play against everything White can try against you.  Those lines are interesting to learn how to play with an advantage in development and initiative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
