1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. dxe6 fxe6 5. Nc3
{ The most common and natural move. But a mistake. } 5... d5
{ Grabbing the center and asking who is playing with the white pieces. Black threatens to play ...d4. }
6. cxd5 { The most common move. } 6... exd5
{ Black's position is dominant: he has the center and a lead in development. He is ready to develop all of his pieces on optimal squares. After ...O-O, the f-file is also an asset. Black's next move is ...d4. From now on, we will see how to deal with White's most common replies. }
7. g3 d4 8. Na4 Bd7
{ Developing with tempo because we are threatening b5 winning the knight. 8...b5 was not possible because of 9.Bg2. }
9. b3 { The only move. } 9... c4 10. Bg2 Bb4+ 11. Kf1 O-O
{ We invite white to take the c4 or the b7-pawn. } 12. Bxb7
{ This pawn is poisoned. } 12... Nc6 13. Bxa8 Qxa8
{ With incredible compensations for the rook, for instance: } 14. Nf3 Bh3+ 15.
Kg1 Ne5
{ We want to take on f3, then play ...Re8, threatening ...Rxe1+ followed by ...Qxf3. }
16. Bf4 Nxf3+ 17. exf3 Re8 { White is paralyzed. } 18. Be3
{ Preventing our idea but this move is just resignation before the resignation... }
18... dxe3 19. fxe3 Rxe3 20. Kf2 Ng4+
{ Opening the f-file and the a8-h1 diagonal for our queen. } 21. fxg4 Re6
{ Qg2# is coming, what to do? } 22. Qf3 { The only move. } 22... Rf6
{ But ...Rf6 ends the game. } *

