1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. dxe6 fxe6 5. g3
{ This is the most common move at the master level. However, Black has no problems at all because of his control over the center. }
5... Nc6 6. Bg2 d5 { Black threatens to play ...d4. } 7. Nh3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  7.Nc3  d4  8.Ne4  e5  Black is already slightly better. We are ready to answer Nxf6+ with ...gxf6. Our space advantage and better pieces will make the difference.   B@@EndBracket@@  7.e3  White wants to prevent d4.  7...d4  We play ...d4 anyway.  8.exd4  cxd4  .  We have better control over the center. Next, we want to finish our development with ...Be7/d6 and ...O-O.   C@@EndBracket@@  7.cxd5  exd5  .  Our central pawns are strong. Next, we want to finish our development with ...Be7/...Bd6 and ...O-O. }
7... d4
{ Black is already slightly better. He has a space advantage and well-developed pieces. The moves ...Bd6 and ...e5 are coming next.  Themodel game will give you an idea about how the game could continue. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 5: Model Games"]
[Black "Mochalov, Evgeny V (2435) vs. Tseshkovsky, Vitaly (2595)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. dxe6 fxe6 5. g3
{ This is the most common move at the master level. However, Black has no problems at all because of his control over the center. }
5... Nc6 6. Bg2 d5 { Black threatens to play ...d4. } 7. Nh3
{ White wants to put his knight on the f4-square. But this does nothing against the ...d4 threat. }
7... d4
{ Black is already slightly better. He has a space advantage and well-developed pieces. ...Bd6 and ...e5 are coming next. }
8. Nf4 Bd6
{ Black develops his bishop and threatens to spoil White's structure. } 9. Nd3
h6 { This clever move prevents the development of the c1-bishop. } 10. e4 e5
{ This looks as if Black was playing with white pieces. } 11. f4 Bg4 12. Bf3 h5
{ Black would like White to take on g4. This capture would weakens the h-pawn. }
13. Nd2 { 13.Bxg4  hxg4  ,  the h-pawn is a big weakness. } 13... Qd7 14. f5 g6
15. h3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 gxf5 17. exf5
{ 17.Qxf5  would be a terrible mistake.  17...Qxf5  18.exf5  e4  and White is doomed. }
17... O-O-O 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 Rdg8
{ Black wants to capture the weak f5-pawn. With his last move, Black prevents g4. Next, he is ready to play ...Ne7. }
20. Kf2 { The final mistake. } 20... Ne7 21. Nxe5 Qxf5+ 22. Qxf5+ Nxf5 23. Bf4
h4 24. gxh4
{ 24.g4  Ne3  ,  the knight is untouchable. ...Rg7-f7 or ...Re7 is coming next. }
24... Nxh4 25. Rhg1 Rxg1 26. Rxg1 Rf8 27. Kg3 Bxe5
{ White resigns. ...Rg8+ followed by ...Nf3+ is coming next. } 28. Bxe5 Rg8+
29. Kf2 Rxg1 30. Kxg1 Nf3+ { The bishop is lost. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 5: Model Games"]
[Black "Georgiou, Antonios (2205) vs. Bayram, Yakup (2260)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. dxe6 fxe6 5. Nc3
{ This is the most common move at the club players' level and a mistake. } 5...
d5 { Black threatens ...d4. } 6. Bg5
{ This does nothing against the ...d4 threat. } 6... d4 7. Ne4 Be7
{ 7...Nc6  is my recommendation in the theory section. However, there is nothing wrong with this move. }
8. Bxf6 Bxf6 { 8...gxf6  was best. Black is already much better. } 9. Nxf6+
{ 9.g3  ,  trying to develop all the pieces quickly was best. } 9... Qxf6 10.
Nf3 O-O
{ Black's position is already crushing. He is ready to develop all his pieces next while White's king is still in the center. }
11. Qd2 h6 { There was nothing wrong with  11...e5  or  11...Nc6  . } 12. e3 e5
13. Bd3 Bh3
{ The simple  13...Nc6  was also strong. However, this move is a good practical choice. }
14. gxh3
{ A blunder.   14.Nxd4  was best.  14...exd4  15.gxh3  Qf3  White's rook is under attack, and White has trouble putting his king into safety. That was Black's concept when he played 11...Bh3. The position is difficult for White, but it was better than the game continuation. }
14... Qxf3 15. Rf1 Nc6 { The last pieces are coming into the game. } 16. Be2
Qxh3 17. O-O-O e4 { The central pawns turn into monsters. } 18. exd4 cxd4 19.
Rg1
{ White is doomed and tries to find some counterplay by sacking the f2-pawn. }
19... Rxf2 20. Rg3 Qxh2 21. Rdg1
{ Now, White sacrifices a piece for counterplay. But this is not enough. }
21... Rxe2 22. Rxg7+ Kh8 23. Qd1 Ne5 24. Qa4 Nd3+
{ ...Re1+ followed by ...Qxg2# is coming. White resigns. } *

