1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. e3
{ This is the second most common move. Here, I recommend we transpose to the Panov Variation of the Caro-Kann Defense. White will have to play with an Isolated Queen Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. This is not something you will meet often. That is why my goal is to keep things simple by recommending you simple lines and ideas. }
3... cxd4 4. exd4 d5 { After cxd5 or ...dxc4, the d4-pawn will be isolated. }
5. Nc3 g6
{ My recommendation is to fianchetto our f8-bishop. From g7, the bishop will exert pressure on the d4-pawn.   In this position, there are 3 moves we need to consider:  6.Qb3  ,  6.cxd5  and  6.Nf3  . }
6. Qb3 e6
{ My recommendation. The normal move is  6...Bg7  , but I prefer to keep things simple with  6...e6  . }
7. Nf3 Bg7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bb5+ Nc6
{ We are ready to castle next. Our bishop is well placed on g7. For instance: }
10. Qa3 { White prevents us from castling. } 10... Qe7+ 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 12. O-O
Be6
{ The plan is to play ...Rhc8 next. This allows us to control the c-file and keep our rooks connected if we need to move our king at some point. The king is well placed in the center and can come to d8 if necessary.  Black went on to win in Shvayger, Y.  2409  vs Nabaty, T.  2692  , 0-1, 2018. }
*

