[White "Theory 6: Model Games"]
[Black "Jean-Luc Costa vs. Judit Polgar"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d5
{ The Kasparov Gambit. We sacrifice a pawn in exchange for a lead in development. }
6. cxd5 Bc5 7. N5c3 { The main move. } 7... O-O 8. g3
{ White wants to play Bg2 and O-O next. } 8... Ng4
{ We attack the f2-pawn immediately. } 9. e3
{ This covers the f2-pawn. But now, we are ready to push ...f5-f4 to undermine White's structure. }
9... f5 10. Bg2
{ 10.Be2  Nd7  11.O-O  Qg5  and Black has the initiative.  We are ready to undermine White's structure with ...f5-f4 and/or ...h5-h4. Our d7-knight is ready to join the attack via f6, from where he can jump on h5 or e4.  White has to be cautious against our incoming attack. Our pieces are well developed and ready to take active measures, while White's pieces are stuck on the first rank. }
10... f4
{ Only Black can be better here. The f4-pawn managed to undermine White's structure @@StartBracket@@g3/f2/e3@@EndBracket@@.   The f4-pawn is untouchable.  11.exf4  Bxf2+  and if @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp4pp/8/2bPp3/5pn1/2N1P1P1/PP3PBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.gxf4  exf4  .   After the logical  11.O-O  fxg3  12.fxg3   12.hxg3  is not possible because of ...Qg5-h5.  11...Bxe3+  12.Bxe3  Rxf1+  14.Qxf1  Nxe3  , Black is much better. }
11. h3 { White wants to kick Black's knight. But now comes: } 11... Nxf2 12.
Kxf2 fxe3+ 13. Ke1 Rf2
{ White's king is under attack. The rook and the bishop are beautiful pieces. Now, Black needs to bring more pieces into the attack. }
14. Rg1 Qf8 { The queen joins the attack. } 15. Qd3 Na6
{ The knight is developed and ready to jump on the b4-square. } 16. a3 Bf5 17.
Be4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Bd4
{ The bishop protects the e5-pawn and frees the c5-square for the knight. } 19.
Bxe3 { 19.b4  was better. } 19... Nc5 20. Bxd4 exd4
{ Black doesn't take the queen in order to open the e-file!  20...Nxe4  21.Nxe4  exd4  22.Nxf2  Qf3  23.Nd2  Qe3+  Black is winning. But the game continuation is stronger. }
21. Qxd4 Re8+ { The last piece joins the action. } 22. Kd1 Qf3+
{ Mate is unavoidable, White resigns. There are a lot of beautiful games by Judit Polgar and this is one of them. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 6: Model Games"]
[Black "Alekseev, Vadim1 (2409) vs. Kolmakov, Pavel (2213)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game will show you how dangerous the Kasparov Gambit can be against unprepared opponents.  White is rated 2409 and Black 2213. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d5
{ The Kasparov Gambit. We sacrifice a pawn in exchange for a lead in development. }
6. cxd5 Bc5 7. d6 { Not a good move but an attractive one. } 7... O-O
{ We castle and invite White to take the challenge. } 8. Nc7 Ne4
{ The f2-pawn is under attack. White must defend it. } 9. e3 Bb4+
{ An important check which forces a white piece on the d2-square. } 10. Bd2
Nxd2 11. Nxd2 Qxd6
{ Black won the d6-pawn, and there is a crushing pin on d2. } 12. Rc1
{ A@@EndBracket@@  12.Nxa8  is met with  12...Rd8  and White is lost.   B@@EndBracket@@  12.Nb5  Qg6  .  White survives, but Black is much better. The pin on the d2-knight is annoying and Black is ready to play ...Rf8-d8 next.   White has problems developing his light-squared bishop because of the pressure on the g2-pawn. For this reason, White will try to put his king in safety by long-castling. But after normal developing moves as ...Nc6, ...Bf5, and ...Rfc8/...Rad8, White will have to be very cautious.   For instance, the game could continue  13.a3  Bxd2+  14.Qxd2  Nc6  15.O-O-O  Bf5  and White's king feels uncomfortable on c1. }
12... Rd8 { The pin will decide the game. } 13. Nxa8
{ White managed to win the a8-rook. But this also costs the game.  13.Rc2  Bf5  White is lost. }
13... Bxd2+ 14. Ke2 Qa6+ 15. Kf3 e4+
{ White's king is lured towards the center. } 16. Kxe4
{ The king is White's most active piece and this is a problem. } 16... Qe6+ 17.
Kf4 Qf5+ 18. Kg3 Qg5+
{ White resigns. This game is interesting to show how lethal the Kasparov Gambit can be.   We sacrifice a pawn for activity. And White has to play accurately for the next 10-15 moves to complete his development and put his king into safety!  The plan with d6 followed by Nc7 seems logical and annoying. I believe this is the idea you will face the most against unprepared players. And the best part is that they will think they tricked you until they understand you are the one who tricked them.  One of our Chessable authors also used this gambit with success  (and in this d6-line)  in Seel, Christian  (2380)  vs. Ganguly, Surya Shekhar  (2541)  , 0-1, 2004. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Theory 6: Model Games"]
[Black "Lexy Ortega vs. Evgeny Ilgizovich Bareev"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d5
{ The Kasparov Gambit. We sacrifice a pawn in exchange for a lead in development. }
6. cxd5 Bc5 7. e3 O-O 8. N5c3 Qe7 9. Nd2 e4
{ ...Bf5 and ...Nd7 are coming next. } 10. a3 a5 { Black wants to prevent b4. }
11. Qc2 Bf5 { Black develops his bishop and protects the e4-pawn. } 12. Be2
Nbd7 13. g4
{ A blunder. White wanted to distract Black from the protection of the e4-pawn. }
13... Nxg4 14. Ndxe4 Qh4
{ The queen and the minor pieces are all well developed. } 15. Bxg4 Qxg4 16.
Qe2 { White would like to trade queens. } 16... Qg2
{ But Black wants to checkmate White's king. } 17. Ng3
{ The knight protects the rook. } 17... Ne5
{ The knight is ready to jump on f3 or d3. } 18. f3 Nxf3+ 19. Kd1 Bh3
{ This move prevents the trade of queens. } 20. Kc2
{ 20.Qxg2  Bxg2  and the rook is trapped. } 20... f5 21. Rd1 Nxh2 22. Qxg2 Bxg2
23. Bd2 { 23.Rd2  is not possible because of  23...Nf3  24.Rxg2  Ne1+  . }
23... Nf3 { The knight comes back in the center. } 24. Na4 Ba7 25. b4 Ne5
{ White's king is exposed and Black takes advantage of it. From e5, the knight is ready to jump on g4/c4 to put pressure on the e3-pawn next.   A logical move like  25...axb4  is possible.  But it would help White to activate his bishop on b4. And then Black's rook on f8 would have to move. This is not what we want! We want to keep pressuring the opponent and keep the initiative! }
26. Bc3 Ng4
{ White resigns. The e3-pawn will fall next. In this position, Black has everything:  - the bishop pair;  - the kingside pawn majority; Black's plan is simple: grab the e3-pawn and push Freddy to make a new queen. And Harry and Garry are ready to help if necessary.   On the opposite, White has nothing:  - The d5-pawn is more a weakness than an asset. White will have to deal with the f-pawn and has no time to take care of the d-pawn.  - White's structure is doomed. If White takes on a5, then the a5 and a3-pawns will be weak. While if he doesn't, the simple ...axb4 will leave White with a weak pawn.  To sum up, White is left with nothing while Black has all the fun. }
*

