1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Be7 6. h3 { White waits. } 6... h5
7. g3 { White doesn't prevent ...h4. } 7... h4 8. g4 Nbd7
{ Black uses all of our typical ideas. } 9. Bg2 Nf8 10. Nge2 Ng6 11. Be3
{ Black is ready to:   Prepare the ...b5 breakthrough. Play ...Nh7 followed by ...Bg5 to exchange his bad bishop. }
11... a6 12. a3 Nh7 { This move prepares ...Bg5. } 13. O-O O-O 14. b4 b6 15.
Qd2 Bg5 { Black managed to trade his bad bishop. } 16. Rab1 Re8 17. bxc5 bxc5
18. Na4 Bxe3 19. fxe3 Qg5 20. Nb6 Rb8 21. Nxc8
{ A mistake. The c8-bishop was not strong. There was no reason to make so many knight moves to trade it on c8. }
21... Rexc8 22. Nc3 Qd8 { Black's queen was doing nothing on the kingside. }
23. Rfc1 Qa5 24. Rb2 Ng5 25. Rcb1 Rxb2 26. Qxb2 Kh7 { This sets a trap. } 27.
Qb7 { And White falls for it. } 27... Qxc3
{ The e3-pawn will fall next. Black doesn't care to lose the c8-rook because his attack is too strong. }
28. Qxc8 Nxh3+ 29. Kh2
{ 29.Bxh3  Qxe3+  30.Kh2  Qg3+  31.Kh1  Qxh3+  32.Kg1  Qe3+  33.Kf1  Qd3+  . }
29... Qxe3 30. Qf5 Qg3+ 31. Kh1 Nf4
{ White's queen is stuck on f5, and ...h3 is coming. } 32. Bf1 Qf3+ 33. Kg1
Qe3+ 34. Kh2 Qf2+ 35. Kh1 h3 36. g5 h2 37. Qg4 Nh4 38. g6+ fxg6 39. Bh3 Ne2
{ There is nothing to do against the threat of ...Ng3+. White resigns. } *

