{ In the game, Black played ...Kxd7. Can you calculate the correct continuation? }
1... bxa2 { Black takes the a2-pawn and wants to promote next. } 2. Be6
{ The f7-pawn is under attack. } 2... Kd8
{ The king avoids any checks on f7 and a7.   2...a1=Q  is a terrible blunder.  3.Qa7+  Qc7  4.Rxf7+  Kd8  5.Rd7+  Kc8  6.Rxd6+  Qd7  7.Qxd7  . }
3. Rxf7 { 3.Qa7  Rb2+  4.Nce2  Qc5+  and Black is winning. } 3... Rb2+
{ A nice check. The goal is to misplace one of White's knights on e2. } 4. Nce2
{ The knight is now misplaced on e2.   4.Nge2  Nc7  ,  an important move. The e8-square is now free for the king @@StartBracket@@there is no Rd7+ threat anymore@@EndBracket@@. Only now, Black is ready to make a queen.  5.Qa7  Qxc3  , while @@StartFEN@@3k4/2n2R2/b2pB1p1/q2Pp1P1/4P3/2N1QP2/pr2NK2/8 w - - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxa2  is well met with  5...Rxe2+  6.Qxe2  Bxe2  . }
4... Rb7
{ The rook comes back to cover the a7-square and to prevent Rd7+. Black will make a new queen next. }
